@node IML-231 " MSG-231  Subject: Attachments and Advertisements
@toc contents

Subject: Attachments and Advertisements
Date:    Sunday, 10 December 1995 14:40:32 
From:    C and/or A Sullivan <ctromanh@uoguelph.ca>


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  


I'm sure some people would appreciate binary attachments and others of 
course do not.  I do not recall voting on this and don't recall if it's 
in the manual that's sent when you first subscribe but I think it's a 
good idea because it could quickly get out of hand if it was given the 
green light.  Not everyone has huge mailboxes and even though binaries 
could be small, what would happen if we all sent one within a few days?  
Somebody's box will fill and overflow and messages will be bouncing 
around like U235 with no heavy water.  Next thing you know: email fission 
- the ASCII gets split from the binary at the point of rejection and 
destroys one random location on the net.  But enough about that.  

On the same token, (Helmy, you can stop reading here) some I'm sure 
appreciate the offers of objects and such at a cost; others may not.  I 
would say I am of the latter persuasion.  I have always viewed this list 
as sort of a two way Public Broadcast System rather than cable.  If 
somebody needs a tutorial or a specific object or texture they can ask 
for it.  Others who respond have a choice: tell the person how to do it 
themselves, tell them where to find it, give it to them.  I don't view 
this as a place to make money off of people who have helped me get to 
where I am.  I look at it as a place to gain skills and knowledge that I 
can market and make money from elsewhere.  There's enough commercials on 
TV and there's enough junk-mail advertisements in my snail-mail box, I'd 
like to try to avoid them in my email box.

Please don't post something that you think some subscribers will take 
exception to and tell them not to respond.

Feel free to respond to this.

Thanks.

*******************************************************************************
*                                                                             *
*      Be prepared to be amazed. -Sully :Amiga4000/030, SGI Indy R4400SC      *
*                                                                             *
*******************************************************************************





