@node IML-249 " MSG-249  Subject: Re: Coil path
@toc contents

Subject: Re: Coil path
Date:    Monday, 11 December 1995 01:13:12 
From:    Charles Blaquiere <blaq@io.org>


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

> From: Jodi Nelson <jodi@c031.focaltech.com.au>
> 
> Thanks Charles
> 
> I have now mastered the art of coil path making which should make for
> some very nice animation.

You're welcome. Of course, if you don't absolutely need a path, (you'd 
need one to Conform an object To Path, for example) here's another way 
you might get a coil-type motion. Warning: untested speculation.

At frame 1, add an empty axis. Position your object at a distance equal
to (the radius of the coil) from the axis, and located along the axis'
Local Y=0. 

At frame 30, move the axis, say +1000 units, along its Local Y. Pick 
Position Bar to make this a keyframe.

Save Changes and go to the Action editor. Add an Associate bar to your 
object, making its coordinates fixed relative to the axis. Then add the 
Rotate20 F/X to the axis, and make it rotate, say 1080 degrees, around 
Local Y.

When you preview the animation, the empty axis will move in a straight 
line, rotating as it goes; and your visible object will follow that 
motion, which will result in a coil path for it. Much simpler than 
defining a real path, and easier to tweak the parameters, too.


                       @{"           Thread          200" link IML-200}
                       @{"  -=> RETURN TO CONTENTS!<=-  " link contents}
@endnode


