@node IML-254 " MSG-254  Subject: Mapping problems
@toc contents

Subject: Mapping problems
Date:    Monday, 11 December 1995 01:49:55 
From:    Charles Blaquiere <blaq@io.org>


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

Nancy,

Imagine's defaults for FlatX/FlatZ mapping apply to an object that would 
appear upright, facing you in the Front view. This matches the way a 
Primitive plane first appears when you create it. Unfortunately, most 
people use flat planes to create gounds, not back walls, and that causes 
much grief among new users.

When flat-mapping a brushmap, the part of the object where the brush 
will be applied lies in the cube of space bounded by the brush's 
positive X/Y/Z axes. When looking at the brush in a view where the 
brush's local Y axis points away from you, the left edge of the brush 
will coincide with the brush's +Z axis, and the bottom of the brush will 
match the brush's +X axis.

You were right in rotating the brush around Local X, but rotating it 90
degrees means it would've looked OK when looking _up_ at the object, as 
seen from below it. I'll make the assumption you were aiming at making 
the brush image appear the same as it did in your paint program, when 
looking _down_ at the landscape. This would entail rotating the brush to 
a _minus_ 90-degree X alignment.

You would then move and scale (in X and Z) the brush so that, in the Top
view, the entire object is contained in the square bounded by the brush's
+X and +Z axes. You'd also move and scale (in Y) the brush so that, in 
the Front view, the entire object was contained between brush Y=0 and 
brush Y=+(Y size).

The brush's Y axis controls the depth where a brush is applied, so that 
if you map a logo to the left side of a truck for example, you'd size 
the Y axis so the brush would not show on the right side of the truck. 
(It would appear reversed -- try it)


