@node IML-256 " MSG-256  Subject: Mapping solution?
@toc contents

Subject: Mapping solution?
Date:    Monday, 11 December 1995 01:55:17 
From:    Charles Blaquiere <blaq@io.org>


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

> From: NancyJcbs@aol.com
> 
> first, I aligned the map axis to x= -90
> 
> then, for SIZE i exchanged the numbers for y & z, but i had to go back
> and increase the thickness of the map (the smallest number) to make it
> cover the sides of the wireframe, even though I'm tiling the map I left
> the model's axis and position as it was. This is very strange, but it
> seems to work. 

Good, I see you got it to work without the reply I just left. Regarding 
tiling: a flat brush will be repeated along its X/Z plane, so the Y size 
has no relationship to tiling; it controls the depth of the brush's 
effect, regardless whether you tile the brush or not.

By the way, Imagine has a bug, which Mike Halvorson has always regarded 
as a feature. Let's call it an inconsistency, then. If you're mapping in 
a cylindrical fashion, say wrapping a marble brush around a vertical 
column, you might be enclined to save memory by using a smaller (in Z) 
brush, and repeating it along Z to cover the entire height of the 
column. Don't. Even though logic dictates it should be supported, 
Imagine disregards the Repeat (and Mirror) buttons in "Cylinder around 
X" and "Cylinder around Z" modes.


                       @{"           Thread          159" link IML-159}
                       @{"  -=> RETURN TO CONTENTS!<=-  " link contents}
