@node IML-270 " MSG-270  Subject: Re: ALERT - Protest Internet Censorship Bills, Tues 12/12/95
@toc contents

Subject: Re: ALERT - Protest Internet Censorship Bills, Tues 12/12/95
Date:    Monday, 11 December 1995 11:12:46 
From:    Ted Stethem <tstethem@linknet.kitsap.lib.wa.us>


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

  There are a couple of misconceptions here that should be cleared up. 
The Internet, as it is now known, was at one time called ARPANET. That is 
because it was a research project of DARPA, the Defense Advanced Research
Project Agency, a US government agency. I won't go into lengthy history 
here, but DARPA put in the Internet "back-bone" and the "back-bone" is 
like the spine in a human body. The Web, the university sites, et al, are 
like the nerves. The Web was developed by a scientist at CERN but it 
still exists on the Internet and cannot operate without it. The packetized 
switching technology which allows the Internet to exist was designed, 
developed, and installed by the US Government. The real kicker here is 
that all this stuff is not "free", which is a widespread misconception. 
The US Government is subsidizing the existence of the Internet, within 
the United States, much like tobacco growers, peanut farmers, bee 
keepers, etc. There is a growing movement, primarily in the Republican 
party, to discontinue the subsidy which maintains the Internet, and allow 
it to be privatized. If, and or when, this happens, you will see a 
definite change in the way the whole thing operates. In fact, if the US 
Government sells off Internet regions like it does radio bands, you will 
definitely see a proliferation of commercials, censorship, access fees, 
and all the other wonderful aspects of capitalism.
  What could also happen is that the packetized switching technology 
rights could be also sold off and then somebody will be making money off 
licensing the rights to use the technology. Of course, the Internet 
outside of the US will still be there, but if it does become privatized 
in the US, then it is possible that "border crossing" checkpoints could 
be set up, tariffs established, customs inspection, etc. Now won't that 
be nice? Its a brave new world. So don't you believe that the Information 
Superhighway can't become a Toll road, with Toll booths along the way.

On Sun, 10 Dec 1995 RobSampson@aol.com wrote:

> In a message dated 95-12-10 14:30:33 EST, you write:
> 
