@node IML-275 " MSG-275  Subject: Re: ALERT - Protest Internet Censorship Bills, Tues 12/12/95
@toc contents

Subject: Re: ALERT - Protest Internet Censorship Bills, Tues 12/12/95
Date:    Monday, 11 December 1995 14:12:55 
From:    Udo K Schuermann <walrus@wam.umd.edu>


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

Bill Boyce <bilboyce@iconz.co.nz> wrote:
> 
> What your congress seems to forget is that the Internet, like it or
> not, is now an international network and many/most of us aren't even
> governed by US law. The Web, their main source of angst, isn't even based
> in the States. It was started/based at CERN in Europe. They can legislate
> all they
> like, but they'll have to cut every phone line and satellite link into and
> out of the States to keep control!

You are correct, Bill, that the Internet is international.  And yet, the
global economy may well be the outlet through which the U.S. might bully
other countries into adopting similar legislation, eventually. Withholding
trade partnerships or imposing higher import taxes, are "nice" incentives,
don't you agree?

Legislating morality is a harebrained scheme, alright, but so was the crap
that the Nazis started a mere six decades ago (legislating what certain
ethnic groups were allowed to own and operate, and what not.) Few people
did anything then, and look what happened!

This is not the time to shrug your shoulders. By not opposing them we
signal our compliance. Even if this censorship movement is doomed to fail,
we empower those who come after to try again, because nobody did anything
the first time around. Can YOU take that risk?

A last thought: if the U.S. wants to impose censorship on a global entity
such as the Net, then they will have to answer to that global entity, i.e.
the whole world. This does involve everyone on the Net, in whatever place
on the planet you happen to be. This is the time for all good 'Netters to
come to the aid of the online world.

