@node IML-287 " MSG-287  Subject: Color Printouts
@toc contents

Subject: Color Printouts
Date:    Monday, 11 December 1995 18:14:00 
From:    mike.vandersommen@caddy.uu.silcom.com (Mike Vandersommen)


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

Thanks to all for the input on Color Hardcopies relating tothe Epson Stylus II a
nd Canon BJC-610.Those Imagine users that need to make a card copy portfolio hav
eexcellent, low cost color ink jet options now!Personally, I decided on the new 
Canon BJC-610. While the Epson Stylu=sII is an excellent printer, there were som
e advantages to the Canonthat pushed me in that direction. Here are my impressio
ns of thisnew printer:* 720x720 dpi output- BJC-610's high res output is absolut
ely  STUNNING! It can print 720x720 on plain paper, but I got  gorgeous results 
with the relatively inexpensive HP CXJetSeries  Cutsheet Paper for color printin
g.  On the HP (expensive) Glossy paper, output is darn near photo  quality. None
 of the banding and pixelations I got with my  HP 550c.  One minor curiosity, ho
wever. I actually got better output on  the HP cutsheet with blacks. On the HP g
lossy the dark black  areas show just a hint of streaking. It might be the paper
 stock,  since I have yet to use Canon specific paper yet. I'm getting  some today.* The BJC-610 uses individual carts for black, cyan, magenta 
and  yellow. If you run out of one color, you just have to buy that  cart, not t
he whole color cartridge.  The printhead mechanism is a separate unit from the i
nk carts,  so you aren't paying to the printhead each time you change ink  carts
, which makes them somewhat cheaper.  While the printhead does have a long life 
span, you will eventually  have to replace it. The upside is it's modular, so it
's pop and  plug. The downside is I've heard it's expensive (like $200) but  hav
en't checked for sure.* The printer driver/utility for Windows is terrific. It's
 intelligen=t  software that senses the printer and monitors it's status. If you
  change paper type, it will not print until you set the printer's  levers to co
rrect positions. It also monitors ink status, and lets  you know when you are ge
tting low. It uses clever voice and animati=on  to keep you updated on whats goi
ng on. Nice touch.* Supports more specialize paper. The BJC-610 supports all sorts of  cool paper products. Like T-Shirt transfers (print your f
avorite  Imagine render on your shirt) and even has a fabric paper for  whatever
 the hell reason. :)* 720x720 Monochrome/Greyscale output is as good as any Lase
r printer  I've seen.* If you need to convince the wife on it, the CD packed wit
h the  Printer is chock full of great programs. It has a commercial  CrossStitch
 program (import pics and printout CS patterns),  Hallmark greeting card app, Cr
ayola Art coloring book for the kiddi=es,  Stationary/Cards/Envelope app, and a 
Stickers and Label program.Final comment: While you can't go wrong with the Epso
n Stylus II forPhoto quality output, I've heard (and read) standard black textpr
intouts are not that hot. The Canon has excellent text output. I'dhighly recomme
nd taking a look at this new entry from Canon. It's onecool color printer!!!ps. 
Expect to pay $100 more for the Canon vs. Epson Stylus II. The    best price I c
ould find was at the Best Buy SuperStore for $512.   /------------------------------           ___   ___  ___   ___  | Mike van der Sommen      
