@node IML-302 " MSG-302  Subject: Net Censorship & IML
@toc contents

Subject: Net Censorship & IML
Date:    Monday, 11 December 1995 23:38:39 
From:    Ted Stethem <tstethem@linknet.kitsap.lib.wa.us>


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

  Some people are complaining that this topic is not relevant to the 
Imagine Mailing List but it is. The current legislation makes the 
service provider liable for the content on the system. Believe it or not, 
Cyberspace is not some whorling vortex of energy in the Gamma quadrant. 
Cyberspace consists of wires, transistors, capacitors, motors, and so on, 
purchased with money. This list exists on a computer, taking up computer 
resources, provided graciously as a forum for a particular topic. The 
legislation that is being presented makes the owner of that computer 
responsible for the material that is on there, regardless if the owner 
had any part of its creation. So, if the legislation becomes law, Unisys 
(look at the IML address) will become responsible for "filtering" all the 
messages that come through the IML, in case the F*** word is there or the 
SH** word, or maybe just any 4 letter word in general, so some minor 
won't join the list and see the words and become a depraved, psychotic 
rapist killer (although that seems to be a side effect of being on the 
IML anyway).  Needless to say, if this legislation becomes law, I doubt 
this list would be maintained at its current cost to you (how much is 
Unisys charging you to be a member of the list?). In actuality, most 
mailing lists in the US will just shut down. Now, is that relevant to this 
list? 

                       @{"           Thread          311" link IML-311}
                       @{"  -=> RETURN TO CONTENTS!<=-  " link contents}
@endnode


