@node IML-305 " MSG-305  Subject: Re: Binary .DXF file?
@toc contents

Subject: Re: Binary .DXF file?
Date:    Tuesday, 12 December 1995 01:19:01 
From:    tl_lab@CESIT1.UNIFI.IT (Tullio Calosci)


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

>Could someone please tell me what a BINARY .dxf file is?
>
>How do I convert one to a standard ascii format .dxf file so I caould 
>read it into Imagine 4.0 (PC)?
>
>Is there a tool freely available for this?
>
>Thank you in advance!

The BINARY .dxf is only an extension of ascii format of dxf.


Take a look a the file wc2pov26.zip.  This converts from/to 
several different formats.  Here is an excerpt from it's readme file.

 WCVT2POV V2.6

This version includes importers for:

      AOFF (*.geo) files
      AutoCAD (*.dxf) files (Only ascii format)
      3D Studio (*.3ds) files
      Neutral File Format (*.NFF) 
      RAW (*.raw) files
      TPOLY (*.tpoly) files
      TrueType fonts (*.ttf) files
      Wavefront (*.obj) files

It also contains emitters for:

      AutoCAD (*.dxf) files
      3D Studio (*.asc) files -- [updated for Truespace V1.0]
      Neutral File Format (*.nff)
      OpenGL (*.c) -- [It will emit a OpenGL C program fragment]
      POVRay V2.2 (*.pov, *.inc)
      PovSB (*.psb) file
      RAW (*.raw)
      TPOLY (*.tpoly)
      VRML V1.0 (*.wrl) 
      Wavefront (*.obj)
bye tullio

(Excuse me for my very bad english)


                       @{"           Thread          278" link IML-278}
                       @{"  -=> RETURN TO CONTENTS!<=-  " link contents}
@endnode


@node IML-306 " MSG-306  Subject: Re: Toystory info / NT version
@toc contents

Subject: Re: Toystory info / NT version
Date:    Tuesday, 12 December 1995 02:38:42 
From:    Falko@aol.com


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

In a message dated 95-12-11 05:06:59 EST, you write:
blaq@io.org

>No, it wouldn't. Rendering speed would be zero, because WinImagine 
>wouldn't run. WinNT programs must be compiled for the processor they'll 
>be running on, so you have, for example, separate versions of Lightwave 
>for Intel and Alpha. Impulse would have to recompile WinImagine for the 
>Alpha, and I can't recall if they mentioned any such plans or not.

There is or will be one exception to this. Digital will release next year a
product called FX32 which will allow win32 programs to run in a "pseudo
native" mode on Digitals Alpha chips running WinNT. Speed is said to be
substantially better than on a Pentium. As I understand it FX32 is more
sophisticated than an emulation product (like SoftWindows). It's more like a
low-level API that allows win32/Intel softare to run on the Alpha. Of course
it may be cheaper to buy a Pentium Pro.

Falko

                       @{"           Thread          660" link IML-660}
                       @{"  -=> RETURN TO CONTENTS!<=-  " link contents}
@endnode


@node IML-307 " MSG-307  Subject: Re: Advertisements
@toc contents

Subject: Re: Advertisements
Date:    Tuesday, 12 December 1995 02:38:48 
From:    Falko@aol.com


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

In a message dated 95-12-10 18:02:45 EST, you write:
helmy@voyager.com

>I understand that some may object to our offer of "3D OBJECT/INTERNET
>SUBSCRIPTION",

I have no problems with a short blurb (that I can read on a single screen, no
less!!) describing/advertising  a Imagine specific product on the IML. The
provisio being brevity! Far more  bandwidth is wasted on questionable
responses to such brief messages.

As to file attachments, some of us (not me though) pay for mail by
storage/quantity/volume. So, I would think the best policy would be to ask
before posting, or establish an attachment size limit. Let's discuss this -
but briefly.

If you do pay for mail in this manner I highly suggest an AOL account or
something similar even if you never use it for anything but e-mail. Think
about it. If you have access to AOL, use Flash Sessions for your e-mail and
attachments, have a 14.4 or 28.8 modem you will _never_ spend more than $9.95
a month. I realize that there are some limitations but these are dissapearing
with rapid expansion of the various networks. I'm sure that the "other" guys
and ISPs have similar deals. Paying for e-mail by volume is out.

No, this is not a plug for AOL. Just an example of my circumstance.

To the question of wasting bandwidth. May I suggest first that some of the
IML members quit pasting the _entire_ message they are responding to in their
responses? And can we get rid of this "chain call" spammer. Sheesh.

Falko

