@node IML-326 " MSG-326  Subject: Re: Smoothing (Shredding)
@toc contents

Subject: Re: Smoothing (Shredding)
Date:    Tuesday, 12 December 1995 13:56:30 
From:    JoBrozycki@vaxsar.vassar.edu (John Brozycki)


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

>In a message dated 95-12-11 23:57:39 EST, you write:
>
>>> to the IML, but haven't found out yet why this is.  Anyway, if you're
>>> planning on blowing up this attack airplane with SHREDDER, you wouldn't
>>>want to be using phong shading on it. 
>>>  
>>You could use the phong shaded object in your animation first and
>>then morph it to the same object without phong shading in the
>>frame before the shredder effect starts.
>
>That might be the problem, since I have used shredder extensively in a couple
>of projects without any problems at all.  Multiple objects over many frames.
>
>Bob......
>Imagine renderings.
>http://home.aol.com/robsampson
>

As the original poster of the above message, I've received the Shredder
error for EVERY animation I've tried if the object being shredded has phong
shading.  At some frame in the animation (and for every frame there after)
the dreaded "setup_phongs:weight err" occurs.  If you have the tenacity to
click through the error requestors, the frame will eventually render with
the shredded bits appearing to shred just fine.  I have tested this in 3.3
and 4.0 on my Amiga 4000 and get the same results with both versions.

SO, THE QUESTION IS: Why can't you (or atleast I) shred an object with phong
shading?  Is it a glitch or is there some bonifide reason you can't do this?
(The "Docs" don't say you can't use phong shading when shredding.)  Are some
people able to shred a phong shaded object through the complete shred effect
without difficulties?  Must one morph to an object sans the phong shading as
the shredding takes effect?  I'm willing to do this but I'd like to know why
I have to.

Thanks,

John Brozycki
JoBrozycki@vassar.edu


                       @{"           Thread          355" link IML-355}
                       @{"  -=> RETURN TO CONTENTS!<=-  " link contents}
@endnode


@node IML-327 " MSG-327  Subject: Re: Toystory info / NT version
@toc contents

Subject: Re: Toystory info / NT version
Date:    Tuesday, 12 December 1995 14:06:14 
From:    schon@freenet.edmonton.ab.ca


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  



On Tue, 12 Dec 1995, Bill Boyce wrote:

> >Running it on NT, as opposed to running the current version in DOS? I 
> >assume the Windows version would be slower, due to the added complexity 
> >of being a Windows program, but I have no way to test or benchmark this. 
> >I'm a regular user, not a beta tester.
> 
> Actually, because WinNT is 32 bit, it could be faster vs DOS. Any techies out 

> there confirm that?

That's like saying that a Semi truck should be faster than a motorcycle 
because it's bigger... It displays a distinct lack of understanding of 
the subject matter.

Running a program under Windows (ANY version) will result is POORER 
performance.

the current misconseption among people that '32-bit is better' is a load 
of crap... the code for the operating system in Win NT is 32-bit, yes, 
but it doesn't mean jack-$hit

DOS >IS< 32-bit... (for all intents and purposes) and you have a hell of 
a lot less overhead than with Windoze.

With DOS, your GUI is part of the program, you can make it as complex as 
you want it, and your program occupies exactly how much space you want... 
with WinDoze, the GUI occupies 8 to 10 Megabytes... Plus your program, 
plus your objects..

With Win NT, you'd need at least 8 TIMES more RAM to approach the speed 
you have with the DOS version (that's right, if you have 8MB right now, 
you'd need a whopping 64MB!!!! to get NEAR what you've got right now) - 
and the closest you'd get would be 75-80% of full power, because of all 
the shit that's happening in the background...

Windoze NT would be a collosal step backwards.


