On Mon, 11 Dec 1995, Charles Blaquiere wrote:

> > From: mikael@pip.dknet.dk
> > 
> > What I  wanted to do with  the black hole was to animate the dust and 
> > gas swirling into the black hole. You know, moving in a spiral 
> > towards the center.
> 
> I feel that you can overlay 4 or 5 semitransparent objects, each 
> rotating and shrinking at its own rate, and the viewer will be fooled 
> into seeing much more complexity than is really there.
> 
> (One of 5 objects: a two-state blue disk, with some filter noise, a 
> radial texture to fade the edges into nothingness, and another radial 
> texture to fade the blue color to white when you get close to the 
> center. First state would have all these textures; second state would 
> see the entire object shrunk and rotated, but the radial textures 
> enlarged to compensate. This way, the noisy blobs will chrink & rotate 
> to simulate gaseous clouds being sucked into the black hole. Create 5 
> such objects, with different shrink/rotation rates, and make sure your 
> Imagine RSDP is set high enough (6?) to allow transparency calculations 
> on so many overlapping objects)
> 
I think if you added motion blur to this it will give it the dual speed 
effect like something going fast and slow at the same time. This would be 
like the time effects one would expect when traveling through one.
