@node IML-363 " MSG-363  Subject: Re: NT/DOS/Amiga version
@toc contents

Subject: Re: NT/DOS/Amiga version
Date:    Wednesday, 13 December 1995 00:53:51 
From:    Jon Galley <JGALLEY@rfc.com>


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

Calm your self.

Let's ask ourselves "What does 'faster' mean?"
Let's say I conceed that YOUR PC will render a DOS imagine pic faster
than a Win imagine pic.  Ok, how does your Dos version (OS) stack up
when we compare some other productivity points:

Batch Rendering
  -- Who care how long it takes if I can render projs and pics at any time I
like.  Batch scripting tools are available if you don't want to write the stub
yourself.

MultiTasking:
  -- Render in Background with Low priority and Model in Forground.  Try
that in Dos.  Works Great in NT with TrueSpace!

Virtual Memory:
  -- While the OS does consume more REAL memory,  You have MANY
times more memory available (at hard drive prices!).  Ever had objects
"VANISH" during DOS rendering?  Would you want the frame even if it
took twice as long to render?

Render Time:
Now let's compare performance of DOS Vs. NT on A PC with (4)  133
Pentium CPUs and a 4 device disk stripe set.  Tomorrow it could be 4
200Mhz PentiumPros, or with an Impulse ReCompile, 4 300Mhz Alphas or
ever a (32cpu) Sequent Server.......

With this kind of "FirePower" NT could best your DOS render by several
ORDERS OF MAGNITUDE!

Fantasy?  Check it out!
 
  The top Dos box?
   Micron's P133 64M 4G SCSI2 for $6300 (with 17" monitor)

   Vs.  -- NT could be as fast as DOS above but with all the goodies
   Micron's P266 64M 4G SCSI2 for $7400 (with 17" monitor)

   Vs.  -- NT could be 4 times faster and with all the other goodies
   Dec Alpha 275 64M 4G SCSI2 for $8600 (with 15" monitor)

PS:
  With mathematically intensive operations 32bit does mean Jack!
  But hey,  if you want to stick with DOS that up to you.


>>> <schon@freenet.edmonton.ab.ca> 12/12/95 02:06pm >>>

On Tue, 12 Dec 1995, Bill Boyce wrote:

> >Running it on NT, as opposed to running the current version in DOS? I 
> >assume the Windows version would be slower, due to the added
complexity  > >of being a Windows program, but I have no way to test or
benchmark this.  > >I'm a regular user, not a beta tester.
>  > Actually, because WinNT is 32 bit, it could be faster vs DOS. Any
techies out  > there confirm that?

That's like saying that a Semi truck should be faster than a motorcycle 
because it's bigger... It displays a distinct lack of understanding of  the
subject matter.

Running a program under Windows (ANY version) will result is POORER 
performance.

the current misconseption among people that '32-bit is better' is a load  of
crap... the code for the operating system in Win NT is 32-bit, yes,  but it
doesn't mean jack-$hit

DOS >IS< 32-bit... (for all intents and purposes) and you have a hell of  a
lot less overhead than with Windoze.

With DOS, your GUI is part of the program, you can make it as complex
as  you want it, and your program occupies exactly how much space
you want...  with WinDoze, the GUI occupies 8 to 10 Megabytes... Plus
your program,  plus your objects..

With Win NT, you'd need at least 8 TIMES more RAM to approach the
speed  you have with the DOS version (that's right, if you have 8MB right
now,  you'd need a whopping 64MB!!!! to get NEAR what you've got right
now) -  and the closest you'd get would be 75-80% of full power,
because of all  the shit that's happening in the background...

Windoze NT would be a collosal step backwards.




