Subject: Re: DOS vs. NT
Date:    Wednesday, 13 December 1995 07:21:41 
From:    craigt@cvillage.com.au (Craig Talbot)


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

>> From: schon@freenet.edmonton.ab.ca
>>
>> With Win NT, you'd need at least 8 TIMES more RAM to approach the speed
>> you have with the DOS version (that's right, if you have 8MB right now,
>> you'd need a whopping 64MB!!!! to get NEAR what you've got right now) -
>
>Now THAT'S an argument I want to see substianted. Please elaborate on
>this overly dramatic statement.
>
>> Windoze NT would be a collosal step backwards.
>
>Right now, I waste more time with DOSImagine closing down the damn thing
>every time I need to tweak some brushmap, than I ever would lose to
>background processes and GUI complexity. I feel the number one issue
>with DOSImagine, is the fact you can't multitask, and coming from an
>Amiga background where the only time my computer has less than 4
>programs open is the first 10 minutes it's turned on, I'll take an
>NTImagine any day.


Hit the nail on the head there Charles, Imagine needs to be multitasking,
it is the only graphics type program I use which does NOT run under windows
or at least run in a DOS window (even 3D Studio Release 4 does that).Why
can't Impulse at least recompile the PC version of Imagine to be DPMI
compatible so that it will work with windows, win 95 and win nt & OS2 in
dos box? It cant be that difficult surely compared with the work they seem
have put into the new versions of Imagine (I'm still working on V2.0).

One can only hope. As for the rubbish about overheads caused by NT posted
on the list, it is partially correct but consider this if you are serious
about 3D rendering, having 32 MB plus is not that unreasonable whether in
DOS or NT.
Personally of course I'd rather work on a Mac but Windows is close enough
and nobody will write stuff like Imagine for the Mac. (sigh)

