@node IML-378 " MSG-378  Subject: Re: NT/DOS/Amiga version
@toc contents

Subject: Re: NT/DOS/Amiga version
Date:    Wednesday, 13 December 1995 08:04:00 
From:    schon@freenet.edmonton.ab.ca


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  



On Tue, 12 Dec 1995, Jon Galley wrote:

> Calm your self.
> 
> Let's ask ourselves "What does 'faster' mean?"
> Let's say I conceed that YOUR PC will render a DOS imagine pic faster
> than a Win imagine pic.  Ok, how does your Dos version (OS) stack up
> when we compare some other productivity points:
> 
> Batch Rendering
>   -- Who care how long it takes if I can render projs and pics at any time I
> like.  Batch scripting tools are available if you don't want to write the stub

> yourself.

I care how long it takes.  Think about it:  you have a project 
deadline... if your frames take 4 times as long to render, will you 
finish in time?  just because you can render 'any time you want' doesn't 
mean that you can render "In time for anything you want"


> MultiTasking:
>   -- Render in Background with Low priority and Model in Forground.  Try
> that in Dos.  Works Great in NT with TrueSpace!

Try using 2 computers (a DX-33 with 8MB works great for modelling... and 
it won't slow your system down... (multitasking with a PC is a joke anyway)

> Virtual Memory:
>   -- While the OS does consume more REAL memory,  You have MANY
> times more memory available (at hard drive prices!).  Ever had objects
> "VANISH" during DOS rendering?  Would you want the frame even if it
> took twice as long to render?

Twice as long?  try 4 times as long.. and no, I probably wouldn't (see 
above for reasons).. virtual memory is a stupid way to cover bad 
programming.  If you need more RAM, BUY MORE!

> Render Time:
> Now let's compare performance of DOS Vs. NT on A PC with (4)  133
> Pentium CPUs and a 4 device disk stripe set.  Tomorrow it could be 4
> 200Mhz PentiumPros, or with an Impulse ReCompile, 4 300Mhz Alphas or
> ever a (32cpu) Sequent Server.......

Ever hear of the phrase "not gonna happen?"  - in order for a program to 
take advantage of multiple processors, it has to be written (from the 
ground up) to take advantage of them... just because something runs under 
NT, does >NOT< make it multi-processor aware... net result:  on your 
"fantasy" boxes, Imagine will STILL be faster under DOS.
 
> PS:
>   With mathematically intensive operations 32bit does mean Jack!
>   But hey,  if you want to stick with DOS that up to you.

If you believe this, then you don't know what 32-bit means... it's that 
simple.




                       @{"           Thread          363" link IML-363}
                       @{"  -=> RETURN TO CONTENTS!<=-  " link contents}
@endnode


@node IML-379 " MSG-379  Subject: Re: DOS vs. NT (was: Re: Toystory info / NT version)
@toc contents

Subject: Re: DOS vs. NT (was: Re: Toystory info / NT version)
Date:    Wednesday, 13 December 1995 08:17:44 
From:    schon@freenet.edmonton.ab.ca


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  



On Wed, 13 Dec 1995, Charles Blaquiere wrote:

> > From: schon@freenet.edmonton.ab.ca
> > 
> > With Win NT, you'd need at least 8 TIMES more RAM to approach the speed
> > you have with the DOS version (that's right, if you have 8MB right now,
> > you'd need a whopping 64MB!!!! to get NEAR what you've got right now) -
> 
> Now THAT'S an argument I want to see substianted. Please elaborate on 
> this overly dramatic statement.

Overly Dramatic?  OK, perhaps... I just get a little carried away... but 
in fact, it's true.

The NT Kernal is >HUGE<  (if you play M:tG, read the flavour text for 
Polar Kraken to understand what I'm talking about)... if you're running 
NT, the kernal takes up over 16MB of RAM _by itself_... read: if you have 
8MB of RAM, the OS has to swap out parts of itself, just to run... this 
'swapping out' (which doesn;t happen in the DOS version at all) degrades 
performance by an ungodly amount (hard drive seek times are measured in 
milliseconds, RAM seek times are measured in nanoseconds...)

I have a LW customer who recently upgraded to and Alpha-NT box with 
64MB... his words to me?  "Man, I knew it took up lots of RAM, but I 
thought 64MB would be TONS!  I can do less than I could with my A4000, 
and that only had 18MB!"

> 
> > Windoze NT would be a collosal step backwards.
> 
> Right now, I waste more time with DOSImagine closing down the damn thing 
> every time I need to tweak some brushmap, than I ever would lose to 
> background processes and GUI complexity. I feel the number one issue 
> with DOSImagine, is the fact you can't multitask, and coming from an 
> Amiga background where the only time my computer has less than 4 
> programs open is the first 10 minutes it's turned on, I'll take an 
> NTImagine any day.

The ability to multitask is, indeed, NT's only saving grace... but as I 
posted previously, it would be cheaper (RAM-wise) to buy a second PC, and 
network them together...



                       @{"           Thread          376" link IML-376}
                       @{"  -=> RETURN TO CONTENTS!<=-  " link contents}
@endnode


@node IML-380 " MSG-380  Subject: Shredder
@toc contents

Subject: Shredder
Date:    Wednesday, 13 December 1995 08:47:38 
From:    jbk4@email.psu.edu (The Prophet)


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

I've heard that shredder doesn't allow for phong shaded objects
but I haven't tested this myself.  But I may have an idea why
shredder wouldn't phong.  With explode, Imagine must create 
edges for each individual triangle, to retain the face as the
object flies apart.  Perhaps Shredder also does this.  It may
create three edges for every face and then create groups of
faces.  Phong won't phong over doubled edges.  I had a similar
problem with an older version of Pixel3D.  Any object I brought
into Imagine from Pixel wouldn't phong until I realized the
duplicate edge problem.  Merge fixed that but I don't think that
will help with shredder.  BTW, newer versions of pixel ask if
you want edge reduction.

Jaeson K.
