@node IML-385 " MSG-385  Subject: Net Censorship--and back to Imagine!
@toc contents

Subject: Net Censorship--and back to Imagine!
Date:    Wednesday, 13 December 1995 11:23:59 
From:    Mike McCool <mikemcoo@efn.org>


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

> "protect" them.  That is where the problem is.  We need to take 
> responsibility for our selves and not leave it up to "Uncle Sam".  

Yes!  There's a great book out now, called BIG BABIES, which treats this 
very theme.  But be forewarned: it's not in the catch-phrase style of the 
Elephant Boy. 

Speak of elephants (segway), I just used someone's genlock method to model a 
nearly decent elephant object.  Still needs work, but hey, it was my 
first real attempt to sink my teeth into the forms editor. 

Y'all probably recall the person's tip, over a year ago, about using two 
amiga's, a genlock, a live chicken and a Rabbi?  

Fellow's name is Andrew (can you believe I actually kept enough of the
footer to remember someone's name?), and I worked on a variation of his
suggestion by genlocking live video onto the screens of the forms editor.
(One amiga's running imagine, the other's running DCTV, with live video). 

I have a little elephant toy, and I set it up with good lighting and
opened one screen at a time in the forms editor, top, front, then right,
and carefully (nah) shifted my elephant toy accordingly for each view. 

Adding a forms object, it's pretty straightforward to drag the points
around and sort of trace the outline of the object, one full-screen view
at a time. 

Whammo, a not altogether funky digitized real world object. 

(See:  I knew there was a good reason not to lose my A500).    

