@node IML-405 " MSG-405  Subject: Re[2]: Toystory info / NT version
@toc contents

Subject: Re[2]: Toystory info / NT version
Date:    Wednesday, 13 December 1995 15:55:47 
From:    spack@mv.us.adobe.com


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

     >It displays a distinct lack of understanding of the subject matter.
     
     I'm sorry, but it is you who does not have an understanding of the 
     subject matter.
     
     >Running a program under Windows (ANY version) will result is POORER 
     >performance.
     
     Not necessarilly.
     
     
     >the current misconseption among people that '32-bit is better' is a 
     >load of crap... the code for the operating system in Win NT is 
     32-bit, >yes, but it doesn't mean jack-$hit
     
     It DOES mean something.  Obviously you have never dealt with segmented 
     architectures.  It takes a lot of time for 16-bit OS's to manage 
     segments within 32-bit address space.  This is the single largest gain 
     a true 32-bit OS or program can obtain.
     
     >DOS >IS< 32-bit... (for all intents and purposes) and you have a hell 
     >of a lot less overhead than with Windoze.
     
     Ohh really.  Then why does DOS have XMS and EMS memory standards?
     Answer:  Because without them DOS cannot access the full 32-bit 
     address space!
     
     
     >With DOS, your GUI is part of the program, 
     
     It's called a command line, it's about 30 years old and it obsolete by 
     *any* standard.
     
     
     >With Win NT, you'd need at least 8 TIMES more RAM to approach the 
     speed >you have with the DOS version (that's right, if you have 8MB 
     right now, >you'd need a whopping 64MB!!!! to get NEAR what you've got 
     right now) - >and the closest you'd get would be 75-80% of full power, 
     because of all >the shit that's happening in the background...
     
     This is utter bullshit.  Are these scientific results of some study?  
     First, you cannot compare NT to DOS for speed.  It's completely 
     illogical!  Does DOS multitask, does it provide a GUI, does it have 
     virtual memory?  NO to all of these.  Sure all of these do eat some 
     CPU cycles, but it is not at a loss of 25% as you would suggest, due 
     to NT's capability to PREMPTIVELLY MULTITASK.
     
     Now in terms of memory, yes you will need more, however your assertion 
     of 64Mb is not correct.  NT requires a minimum of 16Mb; now if Imagine 
     required 8Mb, I would suggest at a minimum a machine with 24Mb.  You 
     could probably squeeze it a bit, but certainly speed would suffer as 
     virual memory kicks in.  The amount of memory it takes to render Scene 
     A is not dependant upon DOS or NT, but how complex your scene is 
     (assuming that a DOS and NT program are built around the same code). 
     
     Now further on the subject of memory.  8Mb is like 1K used to be with 
     the Sinclair ZX80; it's way too little.  Many applications today, on 
     SGI, Win, etc. require 64-256Mb of memory to do *serious* work.  The 
     days of 8Mb are over, 16 is the minimum and will quickly fade as well.
     
     
     >Windoze NT would be a collosal step backwards.
     
     
     Let me conclude that I am not in Love with Windows, but DOS is a 
     collosal "head in the sand" attitude.
     
     
     -Scott
     spack@adobe.com


                       @{"           Thread          485" link IML-485}
                       @{"  -=> RETURN TO CONTENTS!<=-  " link contents}
@endnode


