@node IML-424 " MSG-424  Subject: Re: Toystory info / NT version
@toc contents

Subject: Re: Toystory info / NT version
Date:    Thursday, 14 December 1995 01:05:11 
From:    Falko@aol.com


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

In a message dated 95-12-11 20:32:47 EST, you write:
bilboyce@iconz.co.nz

>Quite apart from the fact that over half the time I spend on a project
>is operating rather than rendering, so a better interface that renders
>slower can still be 'faster' overall. Follow??

On the subject of WinImagine being faster/slower than Imagine for DOS. I've
worked with several programs that had a DOS version and a Windows version. In
almost all cases they work faster in Windows. The only case that was faster
in DOS but less stable if you can believe it, was Autocad which has hardware
specific video drivers for accellerated video. In all other cases the DOS
program was slower. This is primarily due to the lousy interface DOS has to
the video card. Just because you have 1280x1024x8bit display using vesa does
not mean you are using the capabilities of your video card. Most complaints
about windows being slow have to do with a crappy video card and/or driver,
or basic configuration problems. By basic I don't mean simple. I mean core
issues that directly affect windows performance. I should also mention that
our Amiga brethren forward exactly the above argument. "I can get more done
on the Amiga because it multi-tasks and has a better interface". And I agree.
But with windows set up properly (and you should be using Win95 or WinNT if
you are even half-serious about WinImagine). With WinImagine and Win95 or
WinNT you will be able to effectively multi-task, get virtual memory,
hardware accellerated screen redraws, and a better interface. If the renderer
is coded well then it should be just as fast as the dos renderer - providing
you _don't_ have any other programs running. And that includes those neat-o
whiz-bang pretty-but-useless screensavers like After Dark which suck up cpu
cycles like mad (I don't care what Berkeley Software says about activity
sensing, it still eats cpu cycles for breakfast, dinner, lunch and snacks).
If you gotta use a screen saver use a blank screen and DPMS energy saver
features. Windows can really fly if you let it. Anyone who needs some basic
windows advice can e-mail me privately.

Falko

                       @{"           Thread          327" link IML-327}
                       @{"  -=> RETURN TO CONTENTS!<=-  " link contents}
@endnode


