@node IML-432 " MSG-432  Subject: Re: Modeling Black Holes
@toc contents

Subject: Re: Modeling Black Holes
Date:    Thursday, 14 December 1995 05:50:46 
From:    Bill Boyce <bilboyce@iconz.co.nz>


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

> This won't work when the camera gets close. The pixels will disturb all
>realism present. However, to simulate a realistic black hole, use a
>CSG-sphere and add .1 to the fog-lenght and apply the ghost-texture. Play
>around with the settings and *Capow*, you have a real working blak hole!
>

If you really want a working Black Hole, here's an easy tutorial which must
get the award for ease and memory requirements

1. In detail, add an axis.
2. In attributes make your axis a light source, lights values;
 R = -255
 G = -255
 B = -255

 Or different -ve values depending on the desired event horizon

3. Plant tongue firmly in cheek

This actually works - negative values for a light makes pools of darkness
around them. Try it, very freaky.

Used in a scene, this object will 'absorb' light. And just like a real
black hole, the object itself is of course invisible, as the amount of
dust in space is negligible.

Oh, I forgot. Everything in Space animations happens near a large nebula,
so there will be lots of dust :)
(And yes I know Nebula's are actually incredibly thin. Call it poetic
licence, all you science weenies)



