@node IML-433 " MSG-433  Subject: Windows etc
@toc contents

Subject: Windows etc
Date:    Thursday, 14 December 1995 06:01:23 
From:    Bill Boyce <bilboyce@iconz.co.nz>


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

>With Win NT, you'd need at least 8 TIMES more RAM to approach the speed 
>you have with the DOS version (that's right, if you have 8MB right now, 
>you'd need a whopping 64MB!!!! to get NEAR what you've got right now) - 

I'd like to come up with something witty and intelligent, but I'll settle
for COBBLERS!

The point about a GUI versus rendering speed remains. Even if a machine
was four times slower because of it's GUI OS (more like a few % slower)
having multitasking and a GUI would save me a bundle of time. I have
Imagine for my PC at home, and for my Amiga (breadwinner), and the PC
at home is faster than my Amiga for rendering but I dread to think how
all you PC users cope. I rarely use my PC Imagine.

New Topic

And Win95 does multitask nicely and for most users is a vast step up from
Dos and WFW/3.1. It's well behaved, not to memory intensive in todays terms
and is easy to drop to Dos from when necessary - on boot or after Windows.
So don't be put of by all the naysaying, it actually works pretty well. It's
got lots of tricks I wish my Amiga had.

New Topic

And the guy didn't say flat his Amiga renders faster than a PC - he said it
generates palettes faster, which it does. Read before you bite, people! For
some reason palette generation on the PC (I have both) is real slow. 


