@node IML-456 " MSG-456  Subject: Re: Shredder
@toc contents

Subject: Re: Shredder
Date:    Thursday, 14 December 1995 16:11:45 
From:    JoBrozycki@vaxsar.vassar.edu (John Brozycki)


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

 Jaeson Koszarsky wrote on the Shredder effect for Amiga Imagine 4.0:
--------------------------------------------------------------------
>I've heard that shredder doesn't allow for phong shaded objects
>but I haven't tested this myself.  But I may have an idea why
>shredder wouldn't phong.  With explode, Imagine must create 
>edges for each individual triangle, to retain the face as the
>object flies apart.  Perhaps Shredder also does this.  It may
>create three edges for every face and then create groups of
>faces.  Phong won't phong over doubled edges.  I had a similar
>problem with an older version of Pixel3D.  Any object I brought
>into Imagine from Pixel wouldn't phong until I realized the
>duplicate edge problem.  Merge fixed that but I don't think that
>will help with shredder.  BTW, newer versions of pixel ask if
>you want edge reduction.

Jaeson,

Thanks for your response and insight.  It's hard to tell if a tiny flying
piece is phong shaded, so it's possible that (if you click through the phong
error requestors when using shredder and eventually get the frame rendered)
it turns out phong shading hasn't been applied to it at all.  From what I
understand shredding a phong shaded object gives no similar errors on PC
Imagine.  

Assuming your theory is correct, even if you can't phong shade an object's
fragments when it's being shredded, it would *BE NICE* if Imagine was smart
enough to skip the phong shading on shredded pieces without giving you an
error.  As it stands now you can: 

1)Use the object with phong and morph it to an unphonged object at the point
where it starts shredding 
2) Click OK on an error requestor a gazillion times, per frame.

(Maybe Impulse is listening?)


"..and that's all I've got to say about that."
              -"Forrest, Forrest Gumpp"

-John Brozycki
 JoBrozycki@vassar.edu


                       @{"           Thread          429" link IML-429}
                       @{"  -=> RETURN TO CONTENTS!<=-  " link contents}
@endnode


@node IML-457 " MSG-457  Subject: Explosions
@toc contents

Subject: Explosions
Date:    Thursday, 14 December 1995 17:11:10 
From:    RobSampson@aol.com


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

If your looking to make some good explosions in an animation, here is
something to try. Take a primitive sphere and apply cloud texture to it using
bright yellow and orange or red as the colors.  In the attributes requester
make the object bright.  BTW, make sure your primitive sphere has many faces.
 Make this a default state.  Then take the texture and turn all the color off
and set all the filter values to 255.  Make this a new state called clear or
whatever you like.  Now when you use shredder on the object and morph it to
the clear state at the same time you get a nice effect inside of whatever you
are blowing up. Adding some rocket trails that accelerate out of frame along
with utilizing motion blur and having some patience can produce some very
nice results.  Patience is a key however.  Making 4 seconds of animation
using multiple shredder effects and motion blur can take a P90 a couple of
days to churn out.  Previewing the animation in wireframe every 5-8 frames is
essential in making sure that all the objects do go where you want them to
and that your accelerations are all correct in the shredder effects.

Bob.............
Imagine renderings.
http://home.aol.com/robsampson


                       @{"           Thread          467" link IML-467}
                       @{"  -=> RETURN TO CONTENTS!<=-  " link contents}
@endnode


