@node IML-467 " MSG-467  Subject: Re: Explosions
@toc contents

Subject: Re: Explosions
Date:    Thursday, 14 December 1995 23:10:50 
From:    RobSampson@aol.com


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

In a message dated 95-12-14 14:04:43 EST, you write:

>Thanks, mate, for your explosion tips.  I can never know too much about 
>explosions . . . 
>
>

Hehe Imagine is like playing with safe dynamite:)  I also wanted to produce a
shock wave in this effect and so I have made two primitive spheres 48,48 and
stagger points and applied particles to them.  Custom size spheres size 1.0.
 I then made them blue and turned brightness all the way up.  Made that the
default state.  Then I scaled it up about 30x and changed to attributes to
filter 255,255,255 and turned off brightness and made this another state
called big.  (Eh so I'm not so imaginative in naming my states:).  I created
another sphere in the same manner only making it orange vice blue.  I added
this to the animation in the same location as the exploding fireball.  Added
a rotate2 fx on one to spin it 360 over 20 frames and 280 degrees over 20
frames on the other. This was to take advantage of motion blur being on while
rendering.  Thus far it seems to be a rather nice shock wave but it will be
some time before I see a completed animation.  This stuff eats up cpu time
like crazy.  I think it's going to be worth it though.  I suspect this is
going to be a spectacular short animation.

Bob.............
Imagine renderings.
http://home.aol.com/robsampson




