@node IML-493 " MSG-493  Subject: A Spiral Tutorial
@toc contents

Subject: A Spiral Tutorial
Date:    Friday, 15 December 1995 11:11:02 
From:    gregory denby <gdenby@twain.helios.nd.edu>


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  


There have been a couple of questions about spirals shaped objects 
recently.  I checked out the manual and found, yes, only the slightest
mention of how to do this.  So I wrote the following tutorial.  This is
INTERMEDIATE level, and assumes general familiarity with the Detail Editor.

The v.3 Imagine manual decribes the essentials of object extrusion and
replication.  All relevant points are mentioned in a rudimentary form,
and you should be familiar with them.  The following simply extrapolates
and elaborates on the features mentioned in the manual.


Creating helical/spiral objects in the Detail Editor.
Part One, Extruding to length.

It is very easy to create a variety of spiral shapes by using the options 
of the Functions/ Mold/ Extrude command.  Essentially, a value needs to 
be added into the "y" rotation box.  This will yield a turn in degrees 
around the y axis as the object is extruded.

For a quick test, Add/ Primative/ Plane, accept the default 100 units on a
side, and change the vertical and horizontal sections to one.  Pick the 
resulting square, and use the menu Functions/ Mold and select the Extrude 
option (left Amiga\Alt/E).  Accept the To Length method, Length 100.  Make
the sections 36, and the "y" rotation 360, and perform the extrusion.

You now have a twisted square tube, sealed at both ends, which makes one 
complete turn.  Any cross section could have been used.  For example, Add/
 Primative/ Disk, and Pick Points, pick the center point, and Delete it.  
Pick the two points 180 degrees apart on the x axis.  Scale out both along
the x axis, creating two bumps.  Now if you repeat the above extrusion, 
you will have a simple threaded cylinder.

As noted in the manual, the object's axis is the center of the extrusion 
and rotation, and it does not need to be within the object's boundry edges.
Therefore, you can create a tube which rotates around an exterior center.
Try this with a simple disk.  You will note that the tube so produced is
unusually squashed, because its cross section is just pushed in the "y" 
direction.  In order for the tube to coil around the axis, it must be able
to Align to Y.  This brings us to the next section.

2. Extruding to path.

Path extrusion is a powerful method. Either a spline based path or a line 
segment path can be used. Note that line segment paths may be used for 
extrusion and replication, but not for animation. However, the creation of
a smooth spline based path can be difficult, and is not the specific topic
of this tutorial.  Instead,  a further extension of the methods already 
discussed is used.

In the Front view, Add Axis.  For clarity's sake, make sure it is at 
co-ordinates 0,0,0.  Now Add Lines placing one point upon the axis, and 
another some distance away in the "x" direction.  Select Points, Select All,
and Snap to Grid.  You not have a simple horizontal line.  Return to Pick
Objects Mode.  Do Functions, Mold, Extrude.  In a fashion similar to the 
first example, create an extrusion to length.  This time, try a distance 
of 200, y rotation of 720, and Sections 72.  After extrusion, the image in
the front view appears to be a disk with 36 radii.  In the Right or Top views
you will see the twisted plane thus created.  Now go into Pick Points, Drag
Box, and multi-pick the center points.  Delete the 72 points chosen.  You
now have a spiral line.  Return to Pick Objects mode, open the Attributes 
requestor. To make following operation easier, name the line "PATH."

Now add a small disk with just a few sections and a small radius.  Delete 
the central point. Once again, use Functions/ Mold/ Extrude.  This time 
click on To Path.  The default name, PATH, matches the spiral line.  You 
will notice that Align to Y is then un-ghosted.  Click  on Align to Y. 
Again choose Y Rotation of 720, and 72 sections.  Now when you perform the
extrusion, you will have a coil spring like shape whose cross section is 
perpendicular to  PATH.

3.  A bit about Replication.

Replication is Extrude's cousin.  While extrusion joins lines and planes as
it goes, replication simply places copies of the object along the length or
path.  

A handy use for this is making the treads for a spiral staircase.  Add a 
primative disk, 12 sections, radius 36. Delete all but one section.  
Fracture the remaining  radii until you can delete the center point, and be
left with a truncated wedge.  Extrude it one unit to create a solid.  Now 
replicate the object.  Try these parameters.  Length = 104, Copies = 12, 
Y Rotation = 360.  The result will give you the start of a spiral staircase
in scale with common building practice.


  





Hope this helps,
Greg Denby
http://www.nd.edu/~gdenby

                       @{"           Thread          443" link IML-443}
                       @{"  -=> RETURN TO CONTENTS!<=-  " link contents}
@endnode


