@node IML-505 " MSG-505  Subject: IMAGINEERS 'R' US
@toc contents

Subject: IMAGINEERS 'R' US
Date:    Friday, 15 December 1995 17:03:42 
From:    dave@flip.eag.unisysgsg.com (Dave Wickard)


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  


"The Imagine Mailing List-
 Where Computer Artists, Graphics Experts,
 and Rendering Masters roar."



Holiday Howdys Imagineers!  :-)



3 Years and 7 months ago today, I took over the
Imagine Mailing List. Steve Worley, renowned
rendering artist, world champion kickboxer,
and frequent guest host on the Tonight Show 
had asked for a new home for the IML, and I was
honored to be able to offer my humble services to
the Amiga (at that time) graphics community.

Steve allowed me to run the list at my discretion,
and to be perfectly honest, I think overall that we
have created a list that has helped many users
of the Imagine products.

Newer users may not understand the maintenance that
a very active mailing list requires. Long time 
users are more likely to understand the dilemmas
of both technological crowd control, as well as
the determination and time commitment that a mailing
list administrator must have.

Yeah, we have our pompous personalities and our 
snotty retorts to posts, the same as every
newsgroup and mailing list, but truly, I can say 
with some pride that while I have had to privately
reprimand a few people... I have never in 42 months
of daily maintenance, had to ban or remove someone
from the IML. I have never had to turn on a filter
or initiate a kill file regarding someone, or some
subject. For this fact, I must thank each and every
member, past and present of the IML. Your forbearance
of those who annoy you , as well as the ability 
of most of you to self-govern have made my duties 
as administrator much less taxing than they might 
have been.

I truly do not know what my role appears to be as far
as Impulse is concerned. Mike Halvorson has always
been informal and decent to me, even when angry
about attitudes or viewpoints he read on the IML.
I hope that Impulse as a company finds value in what
the Imagine Mailing List offers Imagine users.
Special interest groups have always been extra value
items for users, even if the manufacturers are not
aware of it. (I am not implying that this is the
case with Impulse, but simply saying I hope they 
find my/our efforts commendable and of value to 
Imagine users worldwide.) This was always the intent
of the IML from where I sit. 

I take pride in saying Impulse is a Minnesota company.

Why? Dunno.  :-)  I would take pride if someone down
the street from me won the lottery also, even if it
meant nothing to me personally. Guess it's just one of
those unique bolts that hold me together.

Over the course of my history at the helm of the IML,
we have had the expected wildly swinging subjects whose
tangents led us far from Imagine itself. For the most
part, these are tolerable deviations. It's OK (within
reasonable limits, naturally), since I see the IML as
a forum for open discussions whose *basic* boundaries
are set in stone. To set a concrete barrier that doesn't
allow us to mention "Toy Story" or other popular commercial
applications of computer graphics, would be too
restrictive to be enjoyable. It would leave the IML simply
as a quiz sheet. Straight questions, direct answers.

Bah to THAT crap.   ;-)


I consider you all, far and near, my friends and comrades.
Thank you for sharing with me, your good humor, your
hard fought knowledge, your tips and your tutorials.
Also I must thank you for the many personal communications
and Thank You messages I get on a regular basis.
It's very rewarding to know that people appreciate my
time.

Also, I must thank the Imagine FAQ team and Imagine
Archivists both current and past, Steve Worley 
(Parachuting Instructor, Mr. Nude North America 1993
 and bull fighter extraordinaire), Dale Bennett..
the Sun System Administrator who has graciously
allowed me to maintain the list at
Sperry/Unisys/Paramax/Loral on the Sun system,
"email.eag.unisysgsg.com", and the great folks at
Portal, who have likewise allowed me to migrate the
Imagine Mailing List there, when needed. Needless to 
say, I must also thank Impulse Inc. for a great product
that continues it's evolution. May it continue it's
foward path and delight many more thousands of
customers.

          **********************                                           

At this time, I would like to make what has become
the obvious announcement.

As of January 1, 1996... I will no longer be supporting
or administrating the Imagine Mailing List.

That's the bad news (or at least the bad news to some).
The good news is that sometime in the near future
(January or Febuary), Impulse will be creating it's
own Web Site. I just discussed it with Mike Halvorson
a short while ago and he confirms that they are in process
of setting it up. Currently, he expects it to be a 
moderated site. That, and of course, the site name itself
are still not solid information, but if you are on the
IML at the end of the year, the very last message the 
IML carries will be the confirmation of where the new
Impulse Web Site will be. I will make this announcement
to the entire IML even if it's after the January 1
IML expiration date.

So, now... where do we go from here?

That is simply up to the members of the current IML.
My suggestion is a USENET group, although I will simply
be another reader... I no longer have the time to 
dedicate to the maintenance of the group if it's 
moderated. 

The recent posting has prompted me to make this decision.

The mail that greeted me this morning:
-----
From: "Alex..." <A.Craig@dcs.warwick.ac.uk>
Subject: Help!!!!
Date: Fri, 15 Dec 1995 16:41:01 +0000 (GMT)
Mime-Version: 1.0

Help,

I've managed to CC: a copy of Imagine to the IML - just don't ask
how... anyway, is there anyway you can remove the messages for the IML -
there are 3 of them, titled:

      Imagine (1/3)
      Imagine (2/3)
      Imagine (3/3)

Cheers _very_ much in advance,
                              Alex...
-- 
     \|/      Alexander Craig
    (@ @)     Parallel Systems Group   Mail: A.Craig@dcs.warwick.ac.uk
-oOO-(_)-OOo- University of Warwick    http://www.dcs.warwick.ac.uk/~eezer/

--------------


It was a criminal, cowardly, inexcusable act that
can be called nothing less than robbery. One does not 
"accidentally" send megabytes of information in 
3 seperate pieces of mail. This behaviour creates a 
situation that I am not comfortable about. It casts
me in the role of a involuntary babysitter for 
a child without the ethics to opt for civil behaviour.

That is unacceptable.  

I cannot allow myself to be held with possible liability 
for a fool's actions (unless of course I am the fool 
in question).

Thus, we are left with a bit over 2 weeks left as a group.

Feel free to discuss our future IML options, we have 
enough time to come to a decision. Naturally,  I am 
available as always at my email addresses below.


I will talk to you again, but perhaps not before Christmas,
so I want to wish each and every person on the IML,
reading it directly, as well as in digest/archive form,
online in commercial services as well as those who get it
right from me...

A Joyous and Loving Holiday Season,
A Wonderful Christmas,
A Super 1996.


Take care, folks.



Dave Wickard  (612) 456-2783
dave@flip.eag.unisysgsg.com    
dave@shell.portal.com
dave@minn.net
dave@email.eag.unisysgsg.com
dwickard@eag.unisysgsg.com


"My Brethren Hath Read My Posted Words.
 Now Let Us Bray."   ;-)

-The never-to-be implemented closing on
 the Imagine Mailing list digest version.



