@node IML-521 " MSG-521  Subject: Humour: my biggest blunder
@toc contents

Subject: Humour: my biggest blunder
Date:    Friday, 15 December 1995 21:37:29 
From:    Charles Blaquiere <blaq@io.org>


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

Seeing the unfortunate mistake made by that pirate when he accidentally 
sent Imagine 4.0 to the entire IML in addition to his friend, reminded 
me of something which happened to me 10 years ago.

In engineering school, I was part of the video committee. We had the
entire school wired with monitors and cables, enabling us to, say, hook
up cameras to wall plugs in the 6th floor auditorium and broadcast some
conference all over. When nothing was going on, we'd have messages
scrolling across the screen.  (Nothing fancy: just a rotating drum with
file cards taped on it, facing a camera) All of this was controlled by a
large patchboard in our control room/video committee lounge, which
basically allowed us total flexibility: we could hook up anything to
anything. 

This was in the mid-80's, when most people didn't own VCRs and porno
videos were still a novelty item. At the end of a grueling day, I went to
our little lounge to put on a porno and wind down. It was 6:00 PM, I was
alone in the lounge. A few minutes passed, then the phone rang; it was
the guys from the student "radio station", one floor down. Their tone 
was gently amused.

"Hey Charles, there seems to be some kind of crowd amassing around the 
monitors..."

The scene slowly formed into my head. "Oh... my... GOD!", I yelled, as I
raced back to the patchboard and frantically pulled every cable in sight. 

That day, the message camera output had been looped through the VCR on
its way to the distribution amplifier. My relaxing little porno movie had
been playing on every monitor of every floor of the entire building.
(Even the cafeteria, at supper time) Fortunately, the building was fairly
empty at the time, and engineering students being engineering students, 
no action was taken against me. (It actually gave everyone a chuckle) To 
date, this remains as the most humourous blunder I ever made.



                       @{"           Thread          760" link IML-760}
                       @{"  -=> RETURN TO CONTENTS!<=-  " link contents}
@endnode


