@node IML-523 " MSG-523  Subject: Postscript font source (was: PC TTF Fonts to DXF Converter)
@toc contents

Subject: Postscript font source (was: PC TTF Fonts to DXF Converter)
Date:    Friday, 15 December 1995 23:25:18 
From:    Charles Blaquiere <blaq@io.org>


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

> From: That bloke from HMS <tobs@perihelion.co.uk>
> 
> Also, on the subject of fonts <ducking> where can I get some PS fonts ?
> I'm sure this has been mentioned before but I reckon I must have been
> a bit ambitious on the good old delete key !! Web search for
> 'Postscript' is very "interesting" B-((((.

I'll leave online pointers to others, but if you're willing to shell out
just a small amount of money, I _highly_ recommend a CD-ROM from 
Bitstream, a US company specializing in fonts. They have a "500-font CD" 
which contains professional-quality fonts, all in Postscript and 
TrueType format. Contrary to PD or shareware collections, these contain 
the full international character set, an important factor for a European 
like you. (or a francophone like me) An added plus is that these are 
what I love to call "real fonts for the real world", meaning most of 
them are suitable for body text; only about 5% are outlandishly 
decorative. Again, this is in marked contrast to the novelty "2000 
fonts" collections. This real-world attitude also manifests itself in 
the choice of weights: you won't just get Gill Sans, you'll get it in 
Light, Light Italic, Normal, Italic, Condensed, Bold, Bold Italic, Bold 
Condensed, Extra Bold, Extra Bold Condensed, and Ultra Bold. Granted, 
this means Gill Sans takes up 11 of the 500 slots, but I'd much rather 
have a full palette of Gill Sans to work with, than Normal, Bold, and 9 
fonts that look like wooden planks or snow-capped mountains. Know what I 
mean?

Oh, and the PS fonts import perfectly into Imagine's Spline editor.

Anyway, this is the best bargain I've found for high-quality type. The 
CD-ROM costs around $50 in North America, and Bitstream can probably be 
found on the WWW.

The only downside to the disc is the Bitstream naming convention; font
shapes are not copyrighteable, only their name.  Therefore, companies
like Bitstream which duplicate existing type foundry designs, must use a
different name. It's a drag having "Humanist 521" instead of "Gill Sans"
in your font menu, but for the price, I'll gladly get used to it. Two 
things help greatly: the poster that comes with the disc, showing all 
500 fonts; and the text file found in places like CompuServe, listing 
the standard equivalent to the names of fonts that come with Corel Draw; 
these just happen to be the same Bitstream fonts found on this disc.


                       @{"           Thread          210" link IML-210}
                       @{"  -=> RETURN TO CONTENTS!<=-  " link contents}
