@node IML-524 " MSG-524  Subject: Spiral Motion path
@toc contents

Subject: Spiral Motion path
Date:    Friday, 15 December 1995 23:56:13 
From:    Charles Blaquiere <blaq@io.org>


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

> From: Margaret Copeland <busys@cdsnet.net>
> 
>         I would like to make an 'open' path for motion that is a spiral
> path. I've tried the 'open path' and got nowhere and I've tried making a
> path from axi(s) - no luck. Is there an easier way to do this ? I have a
> jellyfish that I'd like to spiral down a path and I need the path !

Margaret,

I just posted a message regarding a similar subject! You "missed it by 
_that_ much", as Maxwell Smart would've said. Here's a new answer, 
geared to your specific question: (NancyJ was asking about a coil, you 
want a spiral)

Say you want the spiral to begin with a radius of 500 units. You would
add an empty axis 500 units "to the right" of the jellyfish, (as seen
from the fish's point of view) and make the jellyfish the child of the
axis. Create a DEFAULT state, then a START state. Move the jellyfish 500
units, so it's right on top of the axis. Create an END state, with just
"grouping" selected. Save the entire group. 

In Stage, load the group at state START. In Action, add an Actor bar to 
make the group morph to its END state. Then add a Rotate2.0 F/X to the 
group, making it turn as many rotations as you want.

When you animate this, the jellyfish will rotate around the empty axis, 
and the state morph will make the jellyfish move ever-closer to the 
center of rotation. And that, my friends, is perfect spiral motion, and 
"look ma, no path!"


                       @{"           Thread          553" link IML-553}
                       @{"  -=> RETURN TO CONTENTS!<=-  " link contents}
@endnode


@node IML-525 " MSG-525  Subject: Re: No more IML.... No true alternatives either.
@toc contents

Subject: Re: No more IML.... No true alternatives either.
Date:    Saturday, 16 December 1995 00:45:01 
From:    sgiff@airmail.net (Stephen Gifford)


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

>A newsgroup isn't the answer either. Its like watching a TV talk show--
>observer oriented: you know you can call in, but how many of us do? Most
>wont bother, because posting to a newsgroup isnt as direct, immediate,
>or useful. The 'flavor' isnt the same as a direct mailing list. Also,
>you can bet the even more uncontrolled atmosphere of a newsgroup will
>lead to the massave posting of binaries -- of all kinds. And a
>moderated newsgroup will not work for the same reasons the Impulse 
>web site wont work. 

I disagree.  I would rather see the IML on a Newsgroup than a mailing list.
With mail, I have to wait for my computer to download everything including
the unsubscribes, and the Amiga related questions which while not to affend
any Amiga people, are quite boring.  With a Newsgoup, I could visit any time
I liked without having to read junk mail.  Also it would be better if you
had to go away for the Week on vacation, you wouldn't have to unsubscribe.
As it is with up to 50+ mails a day, you can't just leave for the Week.  I
see a lot of advantages to having a Newsgroup over a mailing list.

I am very sad to see this happen.  I have made a lot of friends on this list
over the year and a half that I have been here.  The week that I was down
was very strange feeling for me.  I felt like I had been cut off from the
thing I looked most forward to in the evenings.  Reading the IML mail.

I would also like to thank Dave for his time and efforts put into this list,
great job!

s.g.


