@node IML-542 " MSG-542  Subject: Life, the universe, and everything... oh and the IML death
@toc contents

Subject: Life, the universe, and everything... oh and the IML death
Date:    Saturday, 16 December 1995 05:05:42 
From:    Andrew Herbert <herbert@netcentral.co.uk>


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

OK... here's my words on the departing IML... sorry for the length, but it's 
smaller and a lot more useful than recent posts <grin>.

If you haven't met me before... my name in Andrew Herbert and I've been on 
the list twice with two different internet addresses and during that time 
I've had a good laugh (well sometimes!).  One sunny holiday I got a job 
during the day and it wasn't busy at all so I said.... hey I'll read 
something interesting. Now I was using Imagine at the time... I had given up 
with Videoscape.... YES, THAT LONG AGO !  And I saw some interesting text 
files called IMLArc all about my beloved Imagine so I did a mass print out 
that night of all the messages and read them during my stint at work.... 
natuarally I got better use out of Imagine as a result and it seemed to me 
that the IML was a little world of its own with God (Worley) and all his clan 
with freindly chat banding about the corridors of EMail-dom.

Three and a bit years later I'm still using Imagine and still reading the 
Imagine guides off Aminet... I only got on the internet a year ago... and I 
only used it for the IML.  I thought it was great that I could interact with 
all those people I once knew only as DMP printouts all those years ago 
(naturally SP and co had left).  My only declaration is that I profess to 
have read every IMLArchive on Aminet in full which hasn't made me learn about 
Imagine half as much as I've learnt about people (oh... and Imagine bugs).

Naturaly I am saddened of the departure of the IML and everything that goes 
with it (yes ! even the whines! or even the whines about whines!) but things 
move on and I hope someone takes over or IML goes to USENET (god knows 
what'll happen there !).  My only hope is Imagine still has fanatics... 
Lightwave or Real3D are indestructable, but Imagine will fall down with ease 
if it hasn't got a determined person hiding behind the interface... it's a 
very people orientated product... an afterbirth from the Amiga generation.

Now Imagine goes to PC and finds a whole host of new users wowed by results 
and determined enough not to give up at first sight of Imagine's lowly 
interface, just as I did all those years ago.  To tell you the truth I don't 
think Imagine will last much longer, it's a fine product but I feel the 
windows version will be one of the last incarnations before it dies a slow 
death.  Renderers like Truespace offer more features for less...  and 
Truespace is pretty tame compared to the next generation of spline orientated 
renderers... how long can you hold on to your algolrythms Impulse ?  Not much 
longer I'd Imagine...

I only use Imagine because a) I know how to use it well b) I feel too 
attached to leave c) The people who use do not profess to be "Feature 
Artists" (ie nausiating in the extreme).  I feel the IML death will be a 
serious blow to Imagine's future and I think if Impulse would only treat it 
as a hobbyists program instead of a wannabe SFX wizards dream then it'll 
start going places, but all of this of course requires good public relations 
which I regret to say Impulse lack (Mike H postings as an example).

On a totally different note I am pleased to say the UK Imagine BBS will open 
it's doors soon, it's also a BBS for other renderers too but quite a bit will 
be Imagine.  Each user will have their own directory to upload, so they can 
share pics, objects, and attributes with other users.  I hope it will have a 
freindly atmosphere and I am currently negotiating deals with a computer 
careers sign-up firm so that anyone showing talent in the rendering/design 
department will be looked at by companies wishing to employ or train to do 
that type of work.  The phone number and bits and bobs will be sent to 
everyone replying to this email ::> herbert@netcentral.co.uk.  I have no 
plans for a subscription board and the BBS isn't operational yet (still 
writing ARexx scripts for the entire thing). I don't want this to sound *too* 
much like a gratuitous advert so I'll stop there.

Well 'fraid that's it from me, but one final note to Wickard (If he's reading 
this !) why not give IML 'til Jan 8 1996... at least then it'll have reached 
the big 5 years old!  I've also noticed several references to Worley over the 
past few days... well he is alive and well living on channel #Lightwave on 
IRC if you want to talk to him yourself (nick=SPWorely).

Well... that's it I'm afraid... probrably my last ever post to the IML so 
there ya go.... life, the universe and everything wrapped up in an email... 
it won't help you get a realistic glass attribute (C: R100 G100 B150 
F:200:200:200 IOR: 1.52) but it might make Impulse sit up and notice there 
are Imagine users out there who still love the product and although moan 
about the bugs still use it because of that little IFF, TGA, or TIF they 
managed to squeeze out of it (that's me included).  I offered my services as 
IML archive collector starting 1996... so much for that then!

If I was to give one piece of advice to anyone using Imagine and in the UK 
then ring  01924-366982 (17 bit software) and ask for the "Imagine Video 
Collection", a brilliant showpiece for Imagine by Craig Collins, oh and if 
you track down Craig afterwards... then please contact me!

So long IML... you filled a gaping hole for people support.

                                                      - Andrew Herbert
                                                      Not a professional
                                                      Nor pretends to be
                                                      Just another Imagine
                                                      addict.

