@node IML-543 " MSG-543  Subject: IMAGINEERS 'R' US
@toc contents

Subject: IMAGINEERS 'R' US
Date:    Saturday, 16 December 1995 05:23:00 
From:    m.rubin9@genie.com


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

This is really sad news.

How ironic that as we argued over the government's possible role in
scaring service providers out of business that one jerk has done it
all by himself. It shows how fragile our net "community" really is.

It reminds me of a strange experience I had as a teenager, over 20
years ago, which you will all probably think sounds like a dream.

Word spread through my suburban community outside of Boston that
there was a secret phone number that everyone could call into and
speak to each other, like at a party. As I was kind of socially out
of it, I got this phone number rather late in the game.

When I did dial in one could hear many other voices, kind of like
everyone was inside a huge echoing metal tank where other people's
voices floated around getting louder and softer, randomly. Some
people already seemed to know each other and there were lots of
people calling out although it was kind of hard to communicate, like
being at a crowded party in the dark.

I was totally amazed at what I was hearing and I timidly began to join
in, introducing myself, calling out to the faceless crowd.  People
answered back, asking my name and we all were kind of hysterical with
glee sharing this experience.

Suddenly, off in the seeming distance, a slow siren-like whine began
to grow, like a police car far away. Over the course of the next ten
minutes or so this siren got louder and louder and everyone began to
panic, trying to yell out their names and phone numbers, which rarely
had been exchanged out-loud before. But pretty soon the siren had
obliterated everyone voices and a few minutes later the line went
completely dead. I called the phone company but they denied that it
ever happened.

I've been on the IML for a couple of years and Dave's message brought
this experience all back to me.

I know this story was WAY overdramatic, but I really hope someone else
steps forward to continue the IML (or Dave reconsiders) before Jan 1.
Setting up a newsgroup is a great idea, but it will take months to do
and the amount of background noise is bound to go up. And although I
look forward to an Impulse Web page, a moderated discussion with
their very small staff and CrowBar attitude is bound to be a log jam.

And I wish I had been a more outspoken contributor before now.


Jon Rubin (Floater)
m.rubin9@genie.com



                       @{"           Thread          529" link IML-529}
                       @{"  -=> RETURN TO CONTENTS!<=-  " link contents}
@endnode


@node IML-544 " MSG-544  Subject: Thanks :(
@toc contents

Subject: Thanks :(
Date:    Saturday, 16 December 1995 06:27:34 
From:    jprusins@cybergrafix.com (John Prusinski)


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

Thanks to all who sent me the full text of Dave's farewell message...  
pretty sad.  I've only been on the list for a bit less than a year (after 
using Impulse products since 1987), but I've found it immensely helpful, 
entertaining, occasionally aggravating, and always incredibly human.  I'd 
really miss it if it disappears, so here's hoping Perry (or someone) can 
come through with a new home server, or we can move to a newsgroup.  Either 
of those alternatives strikes me as better than having to rely on the 
Impulse Web site... not that they might not do a good job with that, but I 
have a feeling the free-for-all would be over.  Also, we all know that 
there's real time, and then there's "Impulse time", which means that the 
February launch of said Web site might not necessarily be February '96, if 
you know what I mean...

John.

PS: Dave, I'd like to add a BIG thankyou for all the work you've done 
administering the list for all this time...

 
