@node IML-569 " MSG-569  Subject: Re: Shock waves in animation
@toc contents

Subject: Re: Shock waves in animation
Date:    Saturday, 16 December 1995 16:09:41 
From:    RobSampson@aol.com


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

In a message dated 95-12-16 08:47:38 EST, you write:

>Hmm.. i'm sorry but I must have missed that one.. It seems like an
>intresting idea. If you would be so kind to tell me how you did I would be
>really glad.
>
>Thanks in advance!!
>
>Robert Nilsson
>Flare Produvtions

Well there are two steps to the process.  The first is to get a fireball to
come out of the center of the explosion point without looking like a group of
triangles just blowing into the screen.  Create a primitive sphere with 48,48
and stagger points (more if you like).  I utilized cloud texture,  red and
yellow in colors with brightness turned on and made this the default state.
 I then created another state in which the colors were turned off and the
filter values were all set to 255,255,255.  Now when this object is inserted
into the interior of whatever you are going to explode you can morph it to
invisibility while applying shreddeer to it.  It does need to morph in order
to look more realistic.  At the same time you would want one of those
wonderful shock wave effects like you see on Star Trek and Babylon 5
everytime they blow something up:)  Take the same primitive as I described
above and this time go to particles and select spheres and custome size 1.0.
 Make them blue and set brightness up full.  Make this the default state.
 Make another state in which the filter values all go to 255 and the size is
scaled up by 40x or 50x.  Place this sphere in exatly the same  place as the
fireball in the animation and apply rotate2 to it to spin say 360 over the
frames you have it in the animation.  Repeat the entire process for another
sphere only make it orange or red and only rotate it for 270 degrees.  The
combination of these two spheres growing, expanding and rotating under the
influence of motion blur along with the shreder effect on the fireball make
for a nice explosion.  Don't try this trick on your 386 at home boys and
girls, it is cpu intensive when running shredder and so many effects together
while doing 6-8 frames of motion blur.

Bob.............
Imagine renderings.
http://home.aol.com/robsampson




