@node IML-579 " MSG-579  Subject: Re: Multiple bones - a tut
@toc contents

Subject: Re: Multiple bones - a tut
Date:    Saturday, 16 December 1995 19:14:48 
From:    Valleyview@aol.com


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

>>Can you create a states object that is composed of multiple bones objects?
>eg
>>a human object with arms that aren't contiguous <SP> with the rest of the
>>body, but have bones applied.
>>
>Don't I wish. Please Impulse???

Yes you certainly can do it. The original post kind of suggested two
different wants - either one is possible. (at least on a PC)

One way of looking at your question is that you want one bones object with
detached parts that can fly around in space and be manipulated with bones. No
problem. I suggest you download the mantut.lha tutorial from
ftp://users.aol.com:/valleyview/imagine. Follow that tut doing everything
except don't use fill faces to attach the legs to the body. Make sure you
join the legs to the body the same way and place your bones and face grouping
the same way. Now rotate or move your legs however you want. I haven't gotten
IK to work with detached pieces though but direct manipulation is probably
easier for this anyways.

Now the other way to read your question is just a little trickier to
accomplish but not bad.
You could want distinctly different bones objects, lets say two dancers
moving near each other but not necessarily touching and seperatly controlled
by their own bones structure yet still under one set of states:

Take a finished bone object from the mantut tutorial. Load it in detail -
we'll call it man1. Now load a second one - this will be named man2. Now
here's one trick we have to do - rename the states in man2 to something
unique. We are embedding states within states and all states need to have
unique names. Easy way is to set to a state and create a new state with new
name - then delete the old state.

Position each man in the position you want for your first state. Add an axis,
pick it, and group your men's parent axis to it. Now create a default state
for the axis.(you must have a default state so this name will be the same but
we'll create a copy anyway. IMPORTANT - In all of this axis states you must
pick both the Group and the Shape boxes. This is different then simple bones
objects - ALL states must have the Shape box picked or the embedded states
don't work. Create a unique name state. In group mode still pick a man's
parent axis and use his states to move him to your next position. Do the same
for the other man. You can also use bones and bone update to reposition them.
Pick the axis group and create a new unique state. now animate the axis
states. Both men are moving by their own states but under the axis states. It
works.

Rick

                       @{"           Thread          587" link IML-587}
                       @{"  -=> RETURN TO CONTENTS!<=-  " link contents}
@endnode


