@node IML-601 " MSG-601  Subject: Simulating CHANNELS in Imagine (was: Re: Spiral Motion path)
@toc contents

Subject: Simulating CHANNELS in Imagine (was: Re: Spiral Motion path)
Date:    Monday, 18 December 1995 02:26:12 
From:    Charles Blaquiere <blaq@io.org>


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

On Sat, 16 Dec 1995, Margaret Copeland wrote:

> >I just posted a message regarding a similar subject! You "missed it by 
> >_that_ much", as Maxwell Smart would've said.
> 
>         Well that must have been during the time that I found out that
> Winsock and Windows 95 hate each other (thankyou so much Mr. Gates !!) and I
> had about 800 messages pile up on my server until the 'problem' was solved.
> Thanks for reposting the path stuff. BTW, I am having another problem maybe
> you could help me with. I have my jellyfish grouped. If I use States, I can
> animate the dome seperately and I can set up states for the tenticles but
> .... how does one get the whole thing going in the Action editor ? I gather
> States can only work on objects but can you only have one animated object
> 'set of States' in a group ? Is this a job for Bones ? - but wait my objects
> are grouped and I don't want to join them. Also I can find NO DOCUMENTATION
> whatsoever in the IM.3 manual on what Constrain is ? 


Constraints are documented in the "freeze.txt" disk file.

Bones would certainly work very well with the tentacles; one or two 
bones inside a tentacle would cause the entire tentacle to bend 
gracefully, with little effort on your part.

As for <I believe you're asking about> animating various parts of an 
object using different states, you can't, unless you leave the parts you 
don't want to move, in the same position from one state to another. 
They'll still take up memory, however. (i.e. I believe if you click on 
"Shape" when defining a state, then the shape of the entire group is 
memorized for that state -- you can't have it on or off for various 
subgroups or child objects. It's all or nothing)

DISCLAIMER: the following has not been tested, but my theories are 
usually correct. Anoint me with fragrant oil if my technique makes you 
look like The Second Coming Of Tex Avery, but don't throw blunt objects 
at me if it doesn't work and you've wasted a half-hour of your life. You 
have been warned. <grin>

If you want to, say, animate using different keyframes and timings for 
the dome and some tentacles, you could separate your group into 
individual objects. You would then define states for the various poses 
your dome would assume, and the same for the tentacles. Each part being 
a separate object, you wouldn't even need to have the same amount of 
states in each, allowing more complex motion in one part, while freeing 
you from the overhead that would be required if the object file also had 
to memorize poses from the parts that don't move. Having 
individually-adjustable keyframes for various parts of an object, is one 
aspect of what's called "channels" in high-end software.

You could then bring all the objects into Stage, and animate each with 
the keyframes _it_ requires, regardless what the other parts are doing. 
Then, to have the individual objects move together as if they'd been 
grouped into the Detail editor, just add an "Associate" Action editor 
bar to each <formerly> child object, with the <former> parent object as 
the reference point. This way, each <former> child will move relative to 
the <former> parent, just like when they were actually grouped. This 
technique allows you to have your cake and eat it too: each part has 
different keyframes, but you only need to define the <former> group's 
motion only once, applied to the <former> parent.

Example: The jellyfish group has the dome as the parent, and 3 tentacles 
as the children. You wish to have the tentacles oscillate 3 times, in 
the time it takes the dome to perform one contract/expand cycle.

You ungroup the group. You define two states for the dome, OPEN and 
CLOSED. (That's in addition to the DEFAULT state, which you must always 
create, yet never use in an animation. But you already knew that, right?)

For each tentacle, let's say the motion is more complex, and requires 4 
states, names S1 through S4. (Plus DEFAULT, of course)

When you've saved all objects individually to disk, import them into 
Stage. They should load at the position where they were saved in 
Detail. Save changes, go to Action, and Associate each tentacle to the 
dome. Then, define your keyframes. For example:

OBJECT                FRAME           STATE
-----------   -----           ------
dome          1               OPEN
dome          30              CLOSED
dome          60              OPEN

tentacle      1               S1
tentacle      4               S2
tentacle      10              S3
tentacle      16              S4
tentacle      21              S1
tentacle      25              S2
tentacle      31              S3
tentacle      36              S4
tentacle      41              S1
tentacle      45              S2
tentacle      50              S3
tentacle      54              S4
tentacle      60              S1

tentacle.1    1               S1
tentacle.1    5               S2
etc.

tentacle.2    1               S1
tentacle.2    3               S2
etc.

The cycle is 59 frames long, so you'd render frames 1-59 and leave frame 
60 alone, because when played back, frame 1 (which is a perfect copy of 
frame 60) will appear to follow frame 59 perfectly.

(That last paragraph is standard Imagine procedure, BTW; nothing new or 
Earth-shattering about that. Now back to channels)

As you can see, in the time it takes the dome to close and open once, 
the tentacles perform 3 cycles of states S1 through S4, with slightly 
different keyframes on each tentacle to make the whole thing look much 
more natural. And due to the Associate bars, the objects all move as a 
group. Isn't that a neat idea?

Oh, and you can still use my spiral suggestion, by Associating the 
_dome_ to the moving, rotating empty axis I mentioned in the last 
message. The dome moves relative to the axis, the tentacles move 
relative to the dome, and all viewers will see is a wriggling jellyfish 
on a spiral path. Neat-o!


                       @{"           Thread          131" link IML-131}
                       @{"  -=> RETURN TO CONTENTS!<=-  " link contents}
@endnode


@node IML-602 " MSG-602  Subject: Outputting a animation to videotape
@toc contents

Subject: Outputting a animation to videotape
Date:    Monday, 18 December 1995 02:41:53 
From:    jacob@altair.csustan.edu (Dave Jacob)


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  


I am using a genlocking videocard (GVP super vga genlock for the PC)
to output still pictures to a TV screen. So far, so good. My 
question is if I start outputting animations using this ISA card,
what will be the ultimate limiting factors governing the max 
framerate a card like this will will sustain, and what will it be?

Imagine is good at producing the pictures, but it all falls down
once you need to get those pretty pictures to the outside world... :)
 
Dave.

