@node IML-616 " MSG-616  Subject: Not Whoops..STUPID AND THOUGHTLESS!
@toc contents

Subject: Not Whoops..STUPID AND THOUGHTLESS!
Date:    Monday, 18 December 1995 11:08:56 
From:    "Dan.Maclean" <MACLEDJ@PMITAO.USA.COM>


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

From Dan MacLean:
I don't believe it!Someone emailed a pirated copy of Imagine to the List.  No
t only is it stupid to send pirated material over the Internet, but to send it
to the very people who would know what is going on?!  That's positively goofy.
 Now we all have to pay the price.
 
Having spent at least $1000 over the years to keep my Imagine account up to
date I'm very offended by this practice and would like to see Mike chime in
before the demise of this list.
 
"Honest mistake", there was nothing honest about it and I'm insulted that the
word honest was used at all in that message.  It was a dishonest mistake and a
lot of people were inconvenienced by it (and a few may have lost some $$$
paying for those huge uuencodes!).


                       @{"           Thread          201" link IML-201}
                       @{"  -=> RETURN TO CONTENTS!<=-  " link contents}
@endnode


@node IML-617 " MSG-617  Subject: Re: Questions...
@toc contents

Subject: Re: Questions...
Date:    Monday, 18 December 1995 11:55:02 
From:    Mike McCool <mikemcoo@efn.org>


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

Hey Craig, 

      The mag with the PC version of 3.0 is called COMPUTER ART, and it
is unfortunately available only in UK.  It's from the same folks who
publish PCGamer and a couple of Amiga Disc mags.  They never intended to
distribute that one to the US, and future issues will depend on response. 

      I'm in the same boat as you, trying to get i'beamer friends 
connected to Imagine, and Chris Hall, of the list, was kind enough to 
offer to buy me the mag and send it over the water.  

      He's there, in UK, and all it cost me was some DNA and the slave
rights to my unborn children. (I'm sending him a a demo reel,--but it's
still a hell of a deal, considering that, thanks to Chris, my brother is
now in hog heaven, with Imagine 3.0 running on his new Pentium). 


