@node IML-621 " MSG-621  Subject: Re: Graphics Cards and Imagine
@toc contents

Subject: Re: Graphics Cards and Imagine
Date:    Monday, 18 December 1995 13:43:01 
From:    John Grieggs <grieggs@primenet.com>


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

> 
> CC: grieggs@primenet.com
> 
> Letter from Anders Lundholm to John Grieggs Written 13 Dec 95 At 12:43:08
> O'clock
> 
> Hi John ...
> 
>  JG> Key point - IBM makes some of the slowest and lamest graphics cards on
>  JG> the market. For a massive speed increase, try upgrading to an ATI mach64
>  JG> card, such as the Graphics Ultra Pro Turbo, like I run.  640x480 at 256
>  JG> colors is a pretty low rez.
> 
> It is to be said, that his graphics card and machinery is the newest on the
> market. His mom is working inside IBM's development department and has all
> the right connections. However, you seem pretty sure on your statement and
> the Mach might be a fast graphics card. Key point here is (from my POV)
> that his graphics card run much faster than any Diamond card I've been
> playing around with. As for the Mach, I'm not sure, but his PC kick ass
> generally, but Imagine steeeeeeeeeeenks!
> 
The graphics card won't help his rendering time, it's his animation and
redraw speeds that it will enhance.  To enhance his rendering speed, he
needs to be more concerned with his memory size and speed and his disk
access speed (mostly memory).  The bus architecture also matters - PCI
is a bit faster than VESA, which is substantially faster than ISA.

>  BTW.  I run my GUPT at 1024x768x32bpp.
> 
> ?! .. What's GUPT ?
> 
Graphics Ultra Pro Turbo.  Such a card would enhance his interface and
animation speeds.  The high-end Diamonds aren't too bad either, tho they
are notorious for driver problems.  The Number 9 series is also swift and
has a good rep.

>  JG> With a decent graphics card, your Pentium should animate very fast
>  JG> indeed.
> 
> Are you using 4MB Vram ?!
> 
Yes, I am.  That's what gives me the high, deep rez.  With only 2 meg of VRAM,
you could still get 640x480x32bpp for animations, and 1024x768x256 for work
screen.  32bpp is really 24 bit color, using a mode which is internally set
to use a full 32-bit int for each pixel, for speed.

I can actually run at 1280x1024x32bpp, but a 17-inch monitor isn't really big
enough for routine use of that mode.

>  o
> /#\  Anders Lundholm . Alien Workshop (Tm) . Lund@Hoa.Ping.Dk
>  ZZ Computer Graphics Design . 3D Modeling & Animation
> 
> -- Via Xenolink 1.97, XenolinkUUCP 1.1
> 
_john


                       @{"           Thread          116" link IML-116}
                       @{"  -=> RETURN TO CONTENTS!<=-  " link contents}
@endnode


