@node IML-624 " MSG-624  Subject: Re: IMAGINEERS 'R' US
@toc contents

Subject: Re: IMAGINEERS 'R' US
Date:    Monday, 18 December 1995 14:57:15 
From:    Ted Stethem <tstethem@linknet.kitsap.lib.wa.us>


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

  This statement is not correct.  The software copyright law states that 
a specific copyrighted program can only be INSTALLED on one machine at a 
time. If the requirement was that it only runs on one machine at a time, 
then a person's defense, should he be suspected, would be that he wasn't 
running the software at the same time another person was running that 
same package. Most PC programs have serial numbers imbedded in the code 
specifically for that reason. 
  Your company should check into this, especially if you are running 
programs over a network.  This usually requires a site license. Believe 
me, I have seen a couple of companies busted for this, believing all the 
time they were doing nothing wrong.
  Of course, this is in the US and I see you are in Australia. At this 
time, there is no standard international copyright laws. But I believe 
future agreements of GATT include working out some kind of international 
copyright enforcement.

On Mon, 18 Dec 1995, Darryl Lewis wrote:

> 
> If he and the person he sent it to were partners in business then it's OK.
> The Copyright syas that it can only be run on 1 machine at a time. If they
> never had 2 machines running at once, then it's OK.
> My company usually only has 1 copy of expensive software, which we make
> sure that only 1 person is using at one time (tricky stuff playing with
> UNIX commands on our network ensure that noly 1 person has access at one
> time).
> 
> I'm not sticking up for piracy, but only showing both sides of the coin.
> Remember - Inocent until proven guilty.
> 
> If people really wanted to get a copy of it, they could have gone to that
> warez list that was mentioned last week. 
> 
> 

                       @{"           Thread          639" link IML-639}
                       @{"  -=> RETURN TO CONTENTS!<=-  " link contents}
@endnode


@node IML-625 " MSG-625  Subject: Re: Animation and sound
@toc contents

Subject: Re: Animation and sound
Date:    Monday, 18 December 1995 16:04:16 
From:    jprusins@cybergrafix.com (John Prusinski)


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  


>I would like to do is make the animation with sound effects this time and was
>wondering what the best software and animation format for something like that
>would be.  Is there anything shareware?  What about commercial, and what
>would be the approximate cost?
>
Talking PC...
Not cheap, but I've been using Autodesk Animator Studio (which I believe is 
around $250-300 at this point).  Apart from being a very good 2D animation 
package which will write out in a variety of formats (and is great for 
editing and/or adding effects to Imagine animations), it comes with a sound 
editing program that will let you easily add and sync sound to your anims.

John.

