@node IML-643 " MSG-643  Subject: Keying A Sequence onto Sequences
@toc contents

Subject: Keying A Sequence onto Sequences
Date:    Monday, 18 December 1995 21:35:00 
From:    lund@hoa.ping.dk (Anders Lundholm)


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  


 People who has trouble using fire should take a look a this one.
Using the texture's axis' and a proper atribute can actually make it up for
real working fire. However, this texture has more to it than just the
fire-section. 

The 'Moving Shadow Background On My Cool Sequences' Section:

Render an animation of 500 frames and use this as a luminanze key for your
background. This will look like there's something shadowing for the
display. Now, translate the texture's axis a bit up and left. Re-Render the
entire animation (you could actually let Art Department do something like
moving the image a bit in the same direction, but this will cause banding
in both the right side and the bottom of the sequence). Now, key this new
sequence on top of the existing modified sequence. This will look like cool
clouds blurring the display. It's about 3 of rendering but it sure looks
awesome!

Anyway, here's the plane if people want to play! For newbies, positioning
of texture axis' and sizing can be like breaking nuts with a plastic knife,
and this should hopefully show them how it works.

begin 644 Fire.Iob
