@node IML-661 " MSG-661  Subject: RE:clothes on Humanoid?
@toc contents

Subject: RE:clothes on Humanoid?
Date:    Tuesday, 19 December 1995 05:40:34 
From:    Granberg Tom <tom.granberg@TV2.no>


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

David Nix:
>Fellow Imagineers-
>
>Could someone with a better grasp of mapping and textures drop me or the list
>a few hints on clothing human figures, especially Tim Wilson's Humanoid?
>
>I need to put some fairly specific costumes on some characters, and my limited
>knowlege of mapping is trying my patience...
>
>Im using an Amiga if it makes any difference...
>
>Oh, and on a related note, three cheers for both Dave W. and Perry L. for
>doing the right thing!
>
>Thanks-
>
>Dave Nix

Ok, I guess you want to keep the object intact and not have to split it?!

It is smart, I think, to make a subgroup for each part of the body, one for each
 
leg,one for each arm, etc.

Take your maps and use the wrap z option, and restrict it to the subgroup you 
have ie, pants map to pants subgroup.
Remeber that z is height, x is width and y is depth witch isnt used when you use
 
the wrap z option.
Then edit the texture axis and scale the z axis so that it fits the body part in
 
question.
For the arms you will also need to rotate it.
Then you can lock each map to a state, boom, you can bend the legs and the 
cloathing bends with it.

Hope this shorty helps you understand the mapping tool. 

BTW, I think I will make a tutorial on bitmap mapping and it's secrets to succes
 
on my homepage soon?!?!?!?!?!?

Renderbrandt

