@node IML-672 " MSG-672  Subject: Re: Clothes on Humanoid?
@toc contents

Subject: Re: Clothes on Humanoid?
Date:    Tuesday, 19 December 1995 08:15:52 
From:    RobSampson@aol.com


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

In a message dated 95-12-19 01:06:15 EST, you write:

>Could someone with a better grasp of mapping and textures drop me or the
list
>a few hints on clothing human figures, especially Tim Wilson's Humanoid?
>
>I need to put some fairly specific costumes on some characters, and my
>limited
>knowlege of mapping is trying my patience...

I have Tim's "Humanoids" as well.  (In a blatant plug for Tim I will say
these are a great value considering the amount of work he has done with it
and the very professional manual that comes with them.  He explains certain
sections of Imagine better than Impulse.)  

     The best I have seen for clothing has been done by GreG tsadillas in his
"Communion" and "All the Rage" images.  In both cases he has opted for cloaks
with hoods for obvious reasons, clothing is really difficult to model.  His
"Sardon" image placed boots and pants on a figure.  My guess in this case
(and if I decide to do anything like it in the future) would be (and this
would work for a still shot only) to take the legs section and where the
pants are to be merge the groups after positioning correctly.  Select the
appropriate faces for the pants section and split them into their own object.
 Apply whatever color and texture you desire.  Do the same thing for faces in
the belt area, possibly scaling them up a bit for effect and building and
placing a seperate buckle object on that.  The boots can be done in much a
similar manner, scaled up slightly and for effect slicing sections out to let
the humanoind skin below show through.  You could get a little creative with
this for someting on the chest like a muscle shirt as well.  But if you are
looking to put him in a 3 piece suit, good luck.  You;ll need to do some
tedious modeling and I hope you get payed very very well for doing it.  As
for mapping a pic of a suit onto a humanoid, I don't think you can do it and
make it look right.  You will have to model the clothing somewhat to get
anything that looks decent in my opinion.

Bob.............
Imagine renderings.
http://home.aol.com/robsampson




