@node IML-698 " MSG-698  Subject: Re: Animation and sound
@toc contents

Subject: Re: Animation and sound
Date:    Tuesday, 19 December 1995 20:11:13 
From:    jprusins@cybergrafix.com (John Prusinski)


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

>John,
>    That's interesting that on the PC a user needs to spend $250 for a 
>program to add sound to the anim. Gee, maybe I should sell my Amiga next 
>week to buy a PC, humm. I just assumed that, like on the Amiga side, 
>there are PD programs to do that kind of stuff.
>     Ok, so how big can you make the anims with that program you 
>mentioned? Can you play them back in real time right off the HD?
> Thanks!
>
>

Jim,
There probably are PD programs on the PC that do that, I just don't need 
them because for 2D animation I have the aforementioned Animator Studio, 
which apart from being an excellent 24-bit animation program includes a 
well-thought-out sound editor, as well as other utilities.  I've been an 
Amiga user since '87, and as much as I loved it, I never found a 2D 
animation program with anything like the capabilities of this program, i.e., 
24-bit real-time animation, painting, sprites (animbrushes), and special 
effects over time, multitrack sound syncing, plus many other plusses. (and 
yes, I have OpalVision, DCTV, and DPaint).
You can make anims (flcs, avis, etc.) as big (file size or image size) as 
your HD and RAM permit, and assuming you have a fast machine with a good 
video accelerator you can play them back realtime (in my case, about 15 
fps).  However, since I've been using it mainly for work for video, I 
usually play back anims just as "pencil tests" before I write the files out 
as sequential 24-bit Targa files for import into the PAR.

Hope this answers your questions!

John.

________________________
John Prusinski/CyberGrafix
jprusins@cybergrafix.com
http://www.cybergrafix.com/

"Whoever undertakes to set himself up as judge in the field of Truth and 
Knowledge is shipwrecked by the laughter of the gods."    A. Einstein


