@node IML-709 " MSG-709  Subject: Re: Animation and sound
@toc contents

Subject: Re: Animation and sound
Date:    Tuesday, 19 December 1995 23:41:58 
From:    jprusins@cybergrafix.com (John Prusinski)


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

>I had heard so many horror stories of bugs and memory mis-management
>with Animator Studio that I have stayed with Animator Pro - a great
>program, but w/o sound and oriented to 8-bit flc's and fli's.
>
>It sounds like your doing OK by it. What version are you using? How
>does it do w/24bit animations?
>

I do like it a lot, and have been using it for professional work for some 
time.  I have version 1.1 (I've had it since the first version, and Autodesk 
just sends me CD's with upgrades every time they come out (no need to 
subscribe to a "constant upgrade program" :~)).  There were bugs in it early 
on, but they seem to have ironed out most of them... there are still 
occasional crashes, but they're pretty rare; memory management is still not 
the best... I find it's safer after half a day of intensive work with the 
program to shut it down, quit Windows, and start back up again, because it 
seems that sometimes when you close a project it doesn't always give all the 
memory back, so if this happens a couple of times over several hours of 
working, the available memory becomes less, and the easiest way to clean it 
up is to close down and start up again.
A fairly minor nuisance, and the strengths of the program (for my uses, 
anyway) make up for it...

It saves 24-bit animations as lossless RLE-encoded AVI files, and they play 
back as well as any video on my Pentium (i.e., full-screen with lots of 
detail and movement is pretty jerky).  BTW, I've been an Animator Pro user 
for quite a while as well, but I've pretty much switched over to Studio.

John.
