@node IML-731 " MSG-731  Subject: Re: Rotating csgs
@toc contents

Subject: Re: Rotating csgs
Date:    Wednesday, 20 December 1995 09:02:09 
From:    jbk4@psu.edu (Prophet)


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

>In a message dated 95-12-16 01:40:33 EST, you write:
>
>>> Do CSG spheres NOT work in the cycle editor?
>>> 
>>> I loaded one in (to rotate a planet), but it didn't show up.
>>> 
>>> I followed the same procedure to rotate another object (not CSG), and it
>>> worked.
>>> 
>>> This must be obvious to those who know, but I could find no reference to
>it
>>> anywhere..
>>
>>I hate to answer a question with a question, but: Why were you using the 
>>Cycle Editor? States is much easier, both to set up and to use. =)
>>
>>
>
>Because, newbie that I am, I didn't realize that there was this fx called
>"rotate2".
>
>Anyway, at least I found out that you CAN'T use csg objects in the Cycle
>editor.
>
>Chalk it up.
>
>Nancy
>
>
>
>

The problem with csg spheres lies with the axis scaling.  In order to
create a legit cycle object, your axes must be scaled, rotated, grouped,
and positioned correctly.

The scaling will usually length your z to point the the parent and shrink
x & y.  But with csg spheres, you must scale all axes equally, otherwise
the sphere shrinks.  So, upon moving to Cycle, your spheres don't vanish,
they just shrink, a lot.  

Remember, unless you are ray-tracing, you won't get perfect spheres anyway.
In ScanLine mode, perfect spheres are converted to a default size primitive
sphere.

I must agree that Cycle editor has been made pretty much obselete with
the introduction of states, kinematics, bones, etc.


Jaeson K.
