@node IML-767 " MSG-767  Subject: Meshpaint Demo
@toc contents

Subject: Meshpaint Demo
Date:    Friday, 22 December 1995 01:06:08 
From:    Ted Stethem <tstethem@linknet.kitsap.lib.wa.us>


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

  I recently got a chance to try out the Meshpaint Demo for Windows from 
Positron Publishing and this proggy is a 3D artist's fantasy come true.
  How would you like to take that plain old white Imagine object 
(converted to Meshpaint format) and pretend you are holding it in your 
hand, and you have a paint palette and a multitude of brushes and just 
start painting on that object?  Yeah, take that head object and paint in 
eyeballs with an iris and pupil, paint the lips, paint in some gray 
hairs, paint in some wrinkles. Maybe even paint in a mole or two. Just 
turn the model a quarter turn and put that scar in on the side of the 
head's face.
  Then take the map off the face and put it on a separate window as a 
flat map. Go in and add some pores, maybe some acne scars. And watch the 
texture on the object change at the same time.
  I have seen this done on an SGI Indigo Extreme running Power Animator. 
That's a $40,000 machine running a $25,000 program. And now, that same 
capability is coming to your PC soon. The ability to paint directly on 3D 
objects gives them a look that can make it difficult to distinguish them 
from a real object. What I really like about it also is that it brings 
the skills of an artist and painter back into the world of 3D rendering. 
With OpenGL support becoming more widespread, at affordable levels, and 
features like mesh painting becoming available, it looks like 1996 is
going to be a great year for the 3D artist.

                       @{"           Thread          793" link IML-793}
                       @{"  -=> RETURN TO CONTENTS!<=-  " link contents}
@endnode


@node IML-768 " MSG-768  Subject: VRML conversion
@toc contents

Subject: VRML conversion
Date:    Friday, 22 December 1995 01:26:33 
From:    Tom Ellard <tome@next.com.au>


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

>From: Craig Andera <CANDERA@rfc.com>

>Has anyone found a tool or set of tools that works well for doing Imagine
>to VRML conversion? Best of all would be something that would take a
>staging file and spit out a VRML file, but I doubt the existence of such a
>beast. I'd settle for being able to convert single objects. 

I've been using Fountain, available from the Caligari web site. It loads
Imagine objects.
Big problem is that VRML is not yet a standard - Fountain's VRML is not the
same as some other programs. So when you do the conversion avoid using
textures, they seem to choke other readers. Fountain will let you run for
three months, then I think it expires.
The fastest VRML creator I've used is Virtual Home Space Builder, it allows
all kinds of multimedia attachements, but only if you use its own MUSEUM
format, not VRML. So now I'm needing to convert VRML to MUSEUM. Conversions
go on and on .... 
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
