@toc contents

Subject: Reflections
Date:    Thursday, 28 December 1995 18:10:00 
From:    eduardo.gomez@canrem.com (Eduardo Gomez)


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

Hi.   I  think  I found a bug in Imagine 3.0 (the Amiga version).  I'm
trying  to  build a metal-like object that gets fully transparent in a
series  of  frames  (just  a  way to fade it out).  I'm using a global
brush  map  to  give the metal something to reflect.  It looks good so
far.   Then  it morphs into a similar object, but with no reflectivity
at  all.   The  funny  thing  is  that the object keeps reflecting the
global brush map!  This happens both in scanline and trace modes.  The
reason  that  I  need  no  reflection is because reflectivity seems to
interfere  with transparency (as lon as an object reflects it won't be
totally transparent, am I right?).  I was forced to give up the method
of creating a metalic-looking object by making it reflect a global map
(the  best  option, because the map is not "fixed" to the object), and
try  other  not so elegant approaches, like just wrapping the same map
to the object with low "full scale values" and playing around with the
color  palette  of the map to make it more delicate.  Is there any way
to overcome this problem?  Has anyone noticed it before?

ED.


