@node IML-791 " MSG-791  Subject: Re: PC Essence
@toc contents

Subject: Re: PC Essence
Date:    Friday, 29 December 1995 11:56:37 
From:    Ted Stethem <tstethem@linknet.kitsap.lib.wa.us>


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

  There could be another reason. Maybe you weren't on the IML about 2 
years ago when V2.9 was finally released and then there were a flurry of 
messages about how Essence I would not work with Imagine. To make a long 
story short, Impulse stated the texture format had been changed to allow 
for vastly improved textures and that Essence textures did not comply to 
the well documented Impulse texture standard. Then some guy on the IML 
started investigating the new textures that came with V2.9 and the Essence 
I textures and discovered the "vastly improved" texture format of V2.9 
only had two checksum bytes changed. It certainly appeared that the 
change had been made to specifically make Essence incompatible with 
Imagine. However, that guy (who has long since left the IML in disgust) 
came up with a byte hack that made Essence compatible with Imagine again.
  I haven't investigated and confirmed this, but I believe the 
documentation that came with V4.0 says the entire texture set was 
re-included because there had been another "change" from the V3.1 
textures. So, it could be that the change in the texture format was 
enough that Steve would have had to spend more time making changes and 
recompiling. He is supposed to be doing the entire Essence set for 
Lightwave anyway and maybe he just feels the Imagine market is too much
trouble to deal with. Plus, the Lightwave market is much more professional
and potentially more lucrative.

                       @{"           Thread          448" link IML-448}
                       @{"  -=> RETURN TO CONTENTS!<=-  " link contents}
@endnode


